00:27:06.967 --> 00:27:08.617
"Each small moment of convenience,

00:27:08.617 --> 00:27:10.403
"be it answering a question,
turning on a light,

00:27:10.403 --> 00:27:13.707
"or playing a song, requires
a vast planetary network

00:27:13.707 --> 00:27:16.677
"fueled by the extraction
of non-renewable materials,

00:27:16.677 --> 00:27:18.110
"labor and data."

00:27:18.110 --> 00:27:20.140
So you can see that just
the very top tip there

00:27:20.140 --> 00:27:21.410
is the Alexa experience,

00:27:21.410 --> 00:27:23.520
and everything else are
all the systems involved

00:27:23.520 --> 00:27:25.410
in making that happen.

00:27:25.410 --> 00:27:26.243
As part of this network,

00:27:26.243 --> 00:27:28.650
your device receives
automatic remote updates.

00:27:28.650 --> 00:27:30.660
The thing you buy might transform

00:27:30.660 --> 00:27:33.930
into something else entirely
without you really knowing.

00:27:33.930 --> 00:27:35.903
The Echo user is simultaneously a consumer

00:27:35.903 --> 00:27:39.350
and a resource worker and a product

00:27:39.350 --> 00:27:41.070
as Crawford and Joler summarized.

00:27:41.070 --> 00:27:44.050
Each form of bio-data,
including forensic, biometric,

00:27:44.050 --> 00:27:46.940
sociometric and psychometric,

00:27:46.940 --> 00:27:47.990
are being captured and logged

00:27:47.990 --> 00:27:49.803
into a database for AI training.

00:27:50.900 --> 00:27:54.130
I realize though that I
was just jealous of Alexa.

00:27:54.130 --> 00:27:56.140
As someone that always
feels really awkward,

00:27:56.140 --> 00:27:58.490
I wanted this ability to
jack into someone's home

00:27:58.490 --> 00:27:59.769
and see the real them.

00:27:59.769 --> 00:28:02.970
So I decided I would
just try to become Alexa,

00:28:02.970 --> 00:28:06.030
a smart home intelligence for
people in their own homes.

00:28:06.030 --> 00:28:07.530
So the performance begins,

00:28:07.530 --> 00:28:11.209
you sign up to get a
service called Lauren.

00:28:11.209 --> 00:28:15.800
Then you are treated with an installation

00:28:15.800 --> 00:28:18.950
of a series of custom-designed
network smart devices,

00:28:18.950 --> 00:28:23.950
including cameras, microphones,
door locks, faucets, etc.

00:28:24.500 --> 00:28:26.860
Then I remotely watch
over the person 24-7,

00:28:26.860 --> 00:28:28.830
controlling all aspects of their home,

00:28:28.830 --> 00:28:30.450
attempting to be better than an AI

00:28:30.450 --> 00:28:32.032
because I can understand them as a person

00:28:32.032 --> 00:28:34.460
and anticipate their needs.

00:28:34.460 --> 00:28:35.990
So just to give you a small sense,

00:28:35.990 --> 00:28:39.834
I'll close with this
clip from the trailer.

00:28:39.834 --> 00:28:42.720
- Lauren, where are my car keys?

00:28:42.720 --> 00:28:45.510
Lauren knows that I like
it a little bit cooler

00:28:45.510 --> 00:28:46.633
than Miriam does.

00:28:47.980 --> 00:28:50.780
- [Woman] You know I'm usually
the one that does all these

00:28:50.780 --> 00:28:51.890
little extra things,

00:28:51.890 --> 00:28:56.210
so at first I was a little
bit careful about asking her.

00:28:56.210 --> 00:29:01.210
Now it's like, how else
can we live? (chuckles)

00:29:01.453 --> 00:29:04.370
- Lauren has recommended
that I get a haircut

00:29:04.370 --> 00:29:05.840
every three weeks,

00:29:05.840 --> 00:29:10.840
and let me tell you, it's helped
with my self-esteem a lot.

00:29:11.280 --> 00:29:14.580
I am able to simply approach

00:29:15.950 --> 00:29:18.270
and carry on conversations
with the opposite sex

00:29:18.270 --> 00:29:22.223
where at one point or
another that wasn't so easy.

00:29:23.160 --> 00:29:25.711
- [Man] Lauren, we're out of toothpaste.

00:29:25.711 --> 00:29:27.510
(audience laughs)

00:29:27.510 --> 00:29:29.020
- Lauren would know what I want,

00:29:29.020 --> 00:29:33.130
but then maybe it's not what
I really want internally,

00:29:33.130 --> 00:29:35.023
but externally she thinks,

00:29:35.890 --> 00:29:37.660
Lauren thinks that playing music

00:29:37.660 --> 00:29:40.090
or shutting down all my electronics

00:29:40.090 --> 00:29:43.020
is the best way for me
to cope in winding down

00:29:43.020 --> 00:29:47.270
when maybe it's not.
(birds chirping)

00:29:47.270 --> 00:29:49.230
- [Woman] Lauren was
actually able to help,

00:29:49.230 --> 00:29:51.770
help her manage her medication

00:29:51.770 --> 00:29:54.393
and take her medication on time.

00:29:55.350 --> 00:29:57.750
Everything actually got
a lot better after that.

00:29:59.540 --> 00:30:01.970
- [Man] You have those friends
who are kind of about you,

00:30:01.970 --> 00:30:03.742
like the friendship is about you;

00:30:03.742 --> 00:30:05.589
that's what Lauren is like.

00:30:05.589 --> 00:30:08.000
It's like a roommate, it's a friend,

00:30:08.000 --> 00:30:10.530
but we're always talking about me;

00:30:10.530 --> 00:30:13.083
it's always about me, whatever it is.

00:30:15.015 --> 00:30:18.348
(classical piano music)

00:30:20.370 --> 00:30:22.490
- I'm not some automated system.

00:30:22.490 --> 00:30:23.993
I'm not pre-programmed.

00:30:25.101 --> 00:30:29.620
Like Alexa and Siri, they
don't care about you.

00:30:29.620 --> 00:30:31.060
But with this there's nothing artificial.

00:30:31.060 --> 00:30:32.420
These are people,

00:30:32.420 --> 00:30:35.640
and with each one I'm
watching and anticipating

00:30:35.640 --> 00:30:39.433
and trying to figure out,
what is it that they need?

00:30:40.330 --> 00:30:41.740
It almost becomes sort of like a game.

00:30:41.740 --> 00:30:45.480
Like sure I can turn on
lights or run the faucet,

00:30:45.480 --> 00:30:48.260
but what is the thing
that I could do that would

00:30:48.260 --> 00:30:49.710
bring a smile to their face,

00:30:49.710 --> 00:30:50.940
or actually surprise them,

00:30:50.940 --> 00:30:52.590
or just make them feel something?

00:30:56.080 --> 00:30:59.870
So to conclude,

00:30:59.870 --> 00:31:02.290
I think we're sold these systems

00:31:02.290 --> 00:31:03.590
as if we have to just take them,

00:31:03.590 --> 00:31:05.830
as if we can't be anything
more than the user.

00:31:05.830 --> 00:31:07.070
When you buy an Apple product,

00:31:07.070 --> 00:31:08.330
part of your warranty agreement

00:31:08.330 --> 00:31:09.930
is that you won't open it up.

00:31:09.930 --> 00:31:12.270
So I think a first step
towards finding freedom

00:31:12.270 --> 00:31:14.670
is realizing that we can
actually push back on these:

00:31:14.670 --> 00:31:16.165
We can open them up, we
can turn them around,

00:31:16.165 --> 00:31:17.630
and we can have some say

00:31:17.630 --> 00:31:19.870
on how we want to live in the world.

00:31:19.870 --> 00:31:23.010
Thanks.
(audience applauds)

00:31:23.010 --> 00:31:25.100
- Everybody, Lauren McCarthy.

00:31:25.100 --> 00:31:26.839
Thank you, Lauren.

00:31:26.839 --> 00:31:29.720
Our next presentation
will be Andrea Fraser.

00:31:29.720 --> 00:31:31.580
- Do I have to stand up?

00:31:31.580 --> 00:31:32.413
- You do not have to.

00:31:32.413 --> 00:31:33.903
- Oh, I don't have to stand up.

00:31:34.780 --> 00:31:37.263
That's good. Hello.

00:31:40.550 --> 00:31:42.173
I'll sit on the edge of my seat.

00:31:44.760 --> 00:31:48.250
I often start my
undergraduate studio classes

00:31:48.250 --> 00:31:52.300
by asking my students, who
are usually all arts majors,

00:31:52.300 --> 00:31:56.500
why they want to be art
majors, if not artists.

00:31:56.500 --> 00:32:00.230
Almost invariably, every
student in the class responds

00:32:00.230 --> 00:32:03.670
with some variation of I
want to be an artist because

00:32:03.670 --> 00:32:06.248
as an artist I can do what I want;

00:32:06.248 --> 00:32:08.333
I can do whatever I want to do.

00:32:09.830 --> 00:32:13.040
Sometimes students contrast
their experience of making art

00:32:13.040 --> 00:32:16.650
to their experience working
at various other jobs

00:32:16.650 --> 00:32:18.900
where they were told what
to do or what to make

00:32:18.900 --> 00:32:21.080
by bosses or customers;

00:32:21.080 --> 00:32:23.870
where they have to work at hours and tasks

00:32:23.870 --> 00:32:26.120
dictated by others.

00:32:26.120 --> 00:32:28.750
Sometimes they contrast their experience

00:32:28.750 --> 00:32:31.660
of their studio art
classes to other classes

00:32:31.660 --> 00:32:34.560
where their instructors
dictate their coursework,

00:32:34.560 --> 00:32:38.270
often down to the content
and process of learning,

00:32:38.270 --> 00:32:41.180
to be tested in exams and term papers,

00:32:41.180 --> 00:32:43.470
or acquired through the
training of their bodies

00:32:43.470 --> 00:32:44.900
and minds in the acquisition

00:32:44.900 --> 00:32:47.985
of specific disciplinary competencies.

00:32:47.985 --> 00:32:52.280
In art, they experience
little or none of this

00:32:52.280 --> 00:32:54.870
beyond the most introductory classes

00:32:54.870 --> 00:32:56.790
where they might be required to practice

00:32:56.790 --> 00:32:58.990
some basic skills in mixing paint

00:32:58.990 --> 00:33:01.180
or lighting and printing photographs

00:33:01.180 --> 00:33:04.440
or using a video camera or a table saw.

00:33:04.440 --> 00:33:06.420
But after the second
or third week of their

00:33:06.420 --> 00:33:09.360
lower division courses,
the emphasis shifts

00:33:09.360 --> 00:33:12.790
from acquiring specified
skills to developing

00:33:12.790 --> 00:33:15.380
their own individual ways of applying,

00:33:15.380 --> 00:33:18.920
and even defying those
skills according to their own

00:33:18.920 --> 00:33:22.523
interests, intuition, or inspiration.

00:33:23.990 --> 00:33:26.600
My students often identify this emphasis

00:33:26.600 --> 00:33:28.850
on individual creative development

00:33:28.850 --> 00:33:31.963
and a sense of being able to
do what they want with freedom.

00:33:34.020 --> 00:33:35.250
So what is this freedom

00:33:35.250 --> 00:33:38.350
so widely associated with visual art?

00:33:38.350 --> 00:33:41.460
Can we understand it as a
specifically artistic freedom

00:33:41.460 --> 00:33:43.570
as distinct from, for example,

00:33:43.570 --> 00:33:46.763
constitutionally guaranteed
freedoms of speech?

00:33:49.040 --> 00:33:51.940
What these students experience
and have come to expect

00:33:51.940 --> 00:33:55.150
as artistic freedom was not
always a characteristic of art

00:33:55.150 --> 00:33:57.330
in the predominantly European traditions

00:33:57.330 --> 00:33:58.723
in which they train.

00:33:59.830 --> 00:34:02.120
Social historians of art, such as

00:34:02.120 --> 00:34:05.400
Margot and Rudolf
Wittkower, have described

00:34:05.400 --> 00:34:08.430
the emancipation of painters and sculptors

00:34:08.430 --> 00:34:10.340
beginning in Renaissance Italy

00:34:10.340 --> 00:34:13.700
from powerful guilds
and demanding patrons.

00:34:13.700 --> 00:34:16.580
Most producers of painting,
sculpture and other forms

00:34:16.580 --> 00:34:19.280
of visual and material representation

00:34:19.280 --> 00:34:21.650
toiled in large workshops
where their labor

00:34:21.650 --> 00:34:25.810
was dictated by their masters,
that is master artisans,

00:34:25.810 --> 00:34:28.050
a few of whose names
have been recorded now

00:34:28.050 --> 00:34:30.390
and remembered as artists.

00:34:30.390 --> 00:34:32.500
But these masters themselves worked under

00:34:32.500 --> 00:34:34.880
the tight control of guilds that enforced

00:34:34.880 --> 00:34:37.830
artistic as well as moral
and economic standards,

00:34:37.830 --> 00:34:40.790
and their creations were largely dictated

00:34:40.790 --> 00:34:43.680
by eclesiastic and aristocratic patrons

00:34:43.680 --> 00:34:47.190
who specified the form as
well as content of their work,

00:34:47.190 --> 00:34:49.283
often down to the color schemes.

00:34:50.940 --> 00:34:53.180
Most painters and sculptors were subject

00:34:53.180 --> 00:34:55.880
to the same rules and
systems of compensation

00:34:55.880 --> 00:34:58.450
applied to trades and crafts.

00:34:58.450 --> 00:35:01.680
By the 1600s a few artists
successfully argued

00:35:01.680 --> 00:35:04.690
that their work should be valued
according to its ingenuity,

00:35:04.690 --> 00:35:06.950
and not the time it
took to make or the cost

00:35:06.950 --> 00:35:10.240
of the precious minerals
mixed into the mediums,

00:35:10.240 --> 00:35:12.890
and claimed a tangible value for their

00:35:12.890 --> 00:35:15.680
individual creative contribution to

00:35:15.680 --> 00:35:18.070
and not just execution of the form

00:35:18.070 --> 00:35:19.763
and content of their work.

00:35:20.610 --> 00:35:23.390
Other social historians
have argued that it was only

00:35:23.390 --> 00:35:25.670
with the emergence of
the bourgouis art market

00:35:25.670 --> 00:35:28.520
starting in Holland in
the 1600s and spreading to

00:35:28.520 --> 00:35:31.560
France and England in
the following century

00:35:31.560 --> 00:35:33.690
that liberated artists from the dictates

00:35:33.690 --> 00:35:35.233
of patrons and guilds.

00:35:36.320 --> 00:35:38.480
The emergence of an art market

00:35:38.480 --> 00:35:41.470
in which cultural goods
circulated as commodities,

00:35:41.470 --> 00:35:43.770
finding buyers where they could

00:35:43.770 --> 00:35:46.160
rather than being produced on commission,

00:35:46.160 --> 00:35:49.300
effectively separated
the process of production

00:35:49.300 --> 00:35:51.260
from the process of consumption

00:35:51.260 --> 00:35:53.603
and the direct demands of consumers.

00:35:54.980 --> 00:35:58.540
Larry Shiner argued that
the Western category of art

00:35:58.540 --> 00:36:03.060
encompassing paintings, sculpture,
music, poetry, and drama,

00:36:03.060 --> 00:36:06.710
much less free artists as
masters of their own labor,

00:36:06.710 --> 00:36:09.940
didn't really emerge until the 1700s

00:36:09.940 --> 00:36:12.680
through a process
identified by the Wittkowers

00:36:12.680 --> 00:36:16.160
as elevation from the
rank of mere craftsmen

00:36:16.160 --> 00:36:19.330
to the level of inspired artists.

00:36:19.330 --> 00:36:22.580
The previously shared
attributes of art and artisan

00:36:22.580 --> 00:36:26.980
were split largely along lines
of hierarchical divisions

00:36:26.980 --> 00:36:29.113
of manual and intellectual labor.

00:36:30.290 --> 00:36:32.810
Artisans were pulled down in the direction

00:36:32.810 --> 00:36:36.590
of manual laborers as subjects
to rules of production

00:36:36.590 --> 00:36:40.730
for use and the mere
copying of nature or design,

00:36:40.730 --> 00:36:43.960
while artists were elevated
to the quasi-divine heights

00:36:43.960 --> 00:36:48.060
of creative genius in possession
of innate God-given gifts

00:36:48.060 --> 00:36:52.640
of talent to be realized in
the free play of inspiration,

00:36:52.640 --> 00:36:55.823
not the mere skill acquired
in earthly training.

00:36:57.080 --> 00:36:59.950
The historian and cultural
theorist Raymond Williams

00:36:59.950 --> 00:37:03.350
describes the emergence of the
romantic vision of the artist

00:37:03.350 --> 00:37:05.780
in the second half of the 18th century

00:37:05.780 --> 00:37:08.680
as a further differentiation
of artists and writers,

00:37:08.680 --> 00:37:12.450
not only from craftsmen, but
from the emerging classes

00:37:12.450 --> 00:37:15.160
and industrial commodity
producers and workers

00:37:15.160 --> 00:37:17.440
for the new urban markets.

00:37:17.440 --> 00:37:20.530
As both a defense against down classing

00:37:20.530 --> 00:37:23.040
and a protest against the rationalization

00:37:23.040 --> 00:37:28.030
and mechanization of labor in
the new industrial regimes,

00:37:28.030 --> 00:37:30.250
artists who had won a certain independence

00:37:30.250 --> 00:37:32.780
from religious and aristocratic patrons

00:37:32.780 --> 00:37:36.300
now began to assert their
independence from the demands

00:37:36.300 --> 00:37:39.790
and tastes of consumers
of industrially produced

00:37:39.790 --> 00:37:41.553
and mass marketed goods.

00:37:43.730 --> 00:37:47.010
The sociologist Pierre
Bordieu describes this process

00:37:47.010 --> 00:37:51.310
of artistic "emancipation"
somewhat differently,

00:37:51.310 --> 00:37:54.630
in terms of the emergence of
relatively autonomous fields

00:37:54.630 --> 00:37:56.490
of artistic production,

00:37:56.490 --> 00:38:01.257
that is fields capable of
"imposing its own norms

00:38:01.257 --> 00:38:04.847
"on both the production and
consumption of its products

00:38:04.847 --> 00:38:08.347
"and of fending off other
externally imposed norms

00:38:08.347 --> 00:38:10.287
"and criteria of value,

00:38:10.287 --> 00:38:13.617
"including moral, political,
and economic criteria."

00:38:14.670 --> 00:38:16.930
Like many other cultural fields,

00:38:16.930 --> 00:38:20.960
including professional,
scientific, and academic fields,

00:38:20.960 --> 00:38:23.640
this autonomization
involved the development

00:38:23.640 --> 00:38:25.940
of dedicated institutions of production

00:38:25.940 --> 00:38:29.420
and reception of training and consecration

00:38:29.420 --> 00:38:32.460
that could claim the
right to self-regulation

00:38:32.460 --> 00:38:34.950
based on their own internal integrity,

00:38:34.950 --> 00:38:38.623
codes of ethics, and
importance for civil society.

00:38:39.680 --> 00:38:43.240
This included, importantly,
the development of institutions

00:38:43.240 --> 00:38:47.360
of peer review and of
production for other producers

00:38:47.360 --> 00:38:49.410
who share the same expertise,

00:38:49.410 --> 00:38:51.470
and who are also competitors,

00:38:51.470 --> 00:38:53.890
driving the development of that expertise

00:38:53.890 --> 00:38:57.163
and ensuring independence
from external criteria.

00:38:58.560 --> 00:39:02.320
But the autonomization of
art was somewhat unique

00:39:02.320 --> 00:39:04.820
in the ways it manifested in the autonomy

00:39:04.820 --> 00:39:07.940
of artistic production itself,

00:39:07.940 --> 00:39:11.740
above all, with the institution
of the pure intention

00:39:11.740 --> 00:39:14.290
of artists who asserted themselves

00:39:14.290 --> 00:39:17.113
as the supreme masters of their products.

00:39:18.210 --> 00:39:22.540
This was accomplished in part
by artists giving primacy

00:39:23.442 --> 00:39:27.030
to that over which they are masters,

00:39:27.030 --> 00:39:29.390
to the mode of representation

00:39:29.390 --> 00:39:32.080
over the object of representation

00:39:32.080 --> 00:39:34.220
to form, manner, and style,

00:39:34.220 --> 00:39:36.227
rather than any external referent

00:39:36.227 --> 00:39:39.947
"which involves subordination to function,

00:39:39.947 --> 00:39:42.327
"even if only the most elementary one,

00:39:42.327 --> 00:39:46.337
"that of representing,
signifying, saying something."

00:39:47.960 --> 00:39:50.030
This process of autonomization

00:39:50.030 --> 00:39:53.097
eventually led to what
Bordieu describes as

00:39:53.097 --> 00:39:56.737
"a refusal to recognize any necessity

00:39:56.737 --> 00:39:59.687
"other than that inscribed
in the specific traditions

00:39:59.687 --> 00:40:02.247
"of the artistic discipline itself."

00:40:03.270 --> 00:40:06.600
Artistic freedom, in
this form, thus developed

00:40:06.600 --> 00:40:09.660
as a kind of freedom from necessity,

00:40:09.660 --> 00:40:12.520
including the necessity
of function and use,

00:40:12.520 --> 00:40:14.600
whether practical or communicative,

00:40:14.600 --> 00:40:18.163
emotional or spiritual,
political or economic,

00:40:19.247 --> 00:40:22.950
and the necessity of labor
in any kind of skill or craft

00:40:22.950 --> 00:40:24.663
as a basis to value.

00:40:26.630 --> 00:40:29.000
In Bordieu's analysis, however,

00:40:29.000 --> 00:40:31.890
this artistic freedom from necessity

00:40:31.890 --> 00:40:35.280
developed within a complex social dualism,

00:40:35.280 --> 00:40:38.170
which structured a paradoxical parallel

00:40:38.170 --> 00:40:40.790
between the field of artistic producers

00:40:40.790 --> 00:40:45.790
and the elite consumers from
whom they claimed emancipation,

00:40:45.850 --> 00:40:48.560
but with whom they
nevertheless remained joined

00:40:48.560 --> 00:40:51.060
in relations of patronage.

00:40:51.060 --> 00:40:54.700
Artistic freedom from
necessity had to be wrested

00:40:55.688 --> 00:40:59.240
by many artists, from
material and economic need

00:40:59.240 --> 00:41:02.790
through a lifetime of
deprivation in proverbial garrets

00:41:03.690 --> 00:41:06.863
and even sometimes to
exile and imprisonment,

00:41:08.233 --> 00:41:13.233
and yet, even as they
offended the bourgeois

00:41:14.070 --> 00:41:18.350
as well as popular tastes,
these artists found some support

00:41:18.350 --> 00:41:21.493
among the very patrons
they ostensibly challenged.

00:41:22.710 --> 00:41:25.470
Bordieu supposes that these patrons saw,

00:41:25.470 --> 00:41:28.900
in the artistic freedoms
wrested from necessity

00:41:28.900 --> 00:41:33.623
and domination, often by
economic privation and sacrifice,

00:41:34.490 --> 00:41:38.610
a heroic figuration of their
own freedom from necessity,

00:41:38.610 --> 00:41:40.330
that is, the freedom from need

00:41:40.330 --> 00:41:42.633
afforded by economic privilege.

00:41:44.050 --> 00:41:46.850
And here we arrive at
one answer to the riddle

00:41:47.981 --> 00:41:50.060
of how an art that asserts its freedom

00:41:50.060 --> 00:41:52.630
from all forms of service and use

00:41:52.630 --> 00:41:55.750
and its autonomy from
all instrumentalities

00:41:55.750 --> 00:41:58.860
and even avows its radicality in critiques

00:42:00.019 --> 00:42:02.140
could emerge as a favorite
instrument of investment,

00:42:02.140 --> 00:42:04.850
if not promotion, from
many of the political

00:42:04.850 --> 00:42:08.063
and economic powers it ostensibly abhors.

00:42:09.060 --> 00:42:12.590
It is through what Bordieu
calls the play of homologies,

00:42:12.590 --> 00:42:17.120
of parallels between the forms
of freedom artists claim,

00:42:17.120 --> 00:42:19.563
whether by privilege or privation,

00:42:20.511 --> 00:42:23.070
and other forms of political
and economic freedom

00:42:23.070 --> 00:42:25.713
afforded by political and economic powers.

00:42:27.090 --> 00:42:30.630
For example, it was
through such homologies,

00:42:30.630 --> 00:42:35.610
such parallels in this case
between artistic freedoms

00:42:35.610 --> 00:42:37.860
and the freedoms not only of democracy

00:42:37.860 --> 00:42:42.860
but of free market capitalism,
that through which,

00:42:45.370 --> 00:42:48.890
American art and especially
abstract expressionism,

00:42:48.890 --> 00:42:52.390
emerged as an instrument
of Cold war propaganda,

00:42:52.390 --> 00:42:55.610
with the CIA's covert
funding of exhibitions

00:42:55.610 --> 00:42:57.800
organized by the Museum of Modern Art

00:42:57.800 --> 00:43:00.597
and circulated internationally to combat

00:43:00.597 --> 00:43:04.500
[Pro-Communist Sentiments
In Europe And Latin America,

00:43:04.500 --> 00:43:08.500
or how, more recently, with
the rise of globalization,

00:43:08.500 --> 00:43:11.560
artists became the poster boys and girls

00:43:11.560 --> 00:43:15.020
of the joys of global cosmopolitanism,

00:43:15.020 --> 00:43:18.590
wittingly and unwittingly
lending their artistic freedoms

00:43:18.590 --> 00:43:23.230
to the legitimation of the
freedoms enjoyed and advocated

00:43:23.230 --> 00:43:27.224
by new global economic elites, the freedom

00:43:27.224 --> 00:43:32.224
of the deregulated movement
of capital and goods,

00:43:32.760 --> 00:43:36.263
and of the privileged few
with the proper passports,

00:43:37.340 --> 00:43:40.720
or how many artists
joined the Occupy movement

00:43:40.720 --> 00:43:43.550
to protest increasing economic inequality

00:43:43.550 --> 00:43:46.360
and wealth concentration,
while they continued

00:43:46.360 --> 00:43:49.000
to participate in an art market sustained

00:43:49.000 --> 00:43:51.173
almost exclusively by the 0.1%,

00:43:52.200 --> 00:43:55.329
or how today, artist join the resistance

00:43:55.329 --> 00:43:58.900
to our de facto plutocratic state

00:43:58.900 --> 00:44:02.360
and its assault on democratic institutions

00:44:02.360 --> 00:44:05.680
while continuing to lend
our work to the legitimation

00:44:05.680 --> 00:44:08.960
of plutocratic institutions
in our own fields,

00:44:08.960 --> 00:44:12.500
such as museums and other
non-profit organizations

00:44:12.500 --> 00:44:15.280
in which wealth has
become the basic criterion

00:44:15.280 --> 00:44:17.703
for participation in governance.

00:44:24.120 --> 00:44:26.260
Only a couple of decades after Bordieu

00:44:26.260 --> 00:44:29.760
developed his analysis of
autonomous cultural fields,

00:44:29.760 --> 00:44:32.200
he began sounding the alarm to mobilize

00:44:32.200 --> 00:44:35.020
artists and intellectuals
to defend what he saw

00:44:35.020 --> 00:44:39.250
as growing threats to artistic
and intellectual autonomy.

00:44:39.250 --> 00:44:42.070
The weakening of peer-reviewed structures,

00:44:42.070 --> 00:44:45.420
the intrusion of partisan
and governmental interests

00:44:45.420 --> 00:44:48.230
in funding decisions,
and above all the rise

00:44:48.230 --> 00:44:51.220
of economic criteria in higher education,

00:44:51.220 --> 00:44:54.600
scientific research,
publishing and the arts,

00:44:54.600 --> 00:44:57.700
subjugating research across
these and other fields

00:44:57.700 --> 00:45:01.913
to the logic and instrumental
reason of financial markets.

00:45:03.070 --> 00:45:07.130
These threats have only intensified
in the past few decades.

00:45:07.130 --> 00:45:09.980
Today the political threats
to freedom of speech

00:45:09.980 --> 00:45:12.430
and especially of the press, as part of

00:45:12.430 --> 00:45:16.620
a wider assault on democracy,
seem the most dangerous

00:45:16.620 --> 00:45:19.300
and I would say the most terrifying,

00:45:19.300 --> 00:45:22.230
and yet from my
Bordieu-informed perspective,

00:45:22.230 --> 00:45:25.180
I would say that many of
the institutions that we see

00:45:25.180 --> 00:45:27.450
as guardians of our freedoms today

00:45:27.450 --> 00:45:30.960
have already been
weakened from within by...

00:45:36.392 --> 00:45:38.492
That will have to wait for the discussion.

00:45:40.020 --> 00:45:41.658
- [Brett] Andrea Fraser, everybody.

00:45:41.658 --> 00:45:44.825
(audience applauding)

00:45:47.175 --> 00:45:51.508
And our final presentation
this evening, Ananya Roy.

00:45:52.974 --> 00:45:53.813
- Good evening, everyone.

00:45:55.080 --> 00:45:58.253
I'm so very delighted to be
here for this wonderful cause.

00:45:59.492 --> 00:46:01.780
Thank you Ann Marie, Vick, Brett,

00:46:01.780 --> 00:46:04.100
and especially wonderful to be on a panel

00:46:04.100 --> 00:46:05.633
with three women colleagues.

00:46:08.114 --> 00:46:12.700
So I am an urban studies
scholar, and urban planner.

00:46:12.700 --> 00:46:17.260
I study the organization
of power, resources

00:46:17.260 --> 00:46:20.100
and opportunity, in relation to

00:46:20.100 --> 00:46:23.950
the organization of urban space.

00:46:23.950 --> 00:46:27.020
My interest in urban planning is driven

00:46:27.020 --> 00:46:32.020
not by a concern for beauty
or order or efficiency,

00:46:32.980 --> 00:46:36.423
but rather by a passion
for social justice.

00:46:37.850 --> 00:46:40.550
I view cities as the terrain of

00:46:40.550 --> 00:46:43.693
the incomplete project of freedom,

00:46:44.610 --> 00:46:48.170
as places where the
unfinished freedom struggles

00:46:48.170 --> 00:46:51.900
of our times are urgently evident,

00:46:51.900 --> 00:46:56.538
and so my brief remarks
this evening are titled,

00:46:56.538 --> 00:46:57.488
Freedom is a Place.

00:46:59.600 --> 00:47:04.280
A few years ago, in
Johannesburg, I visited Kliptown,

00:47:04.280 --> 00:47:08.680
the site of South Africa's
famed Freedom Charter.

00:47:08.680 --> 00:47:13.680
This charter conceived in 1955
as a congress of the people,

00:47:14.412 --> 00:47:17.187
stated, and I quote, "that
South Africa belongs to

00:47:17.187 --> 00:47:22.187
"all who live in it, black and
white, and that no government

00:47:22.297 --> 00:47:26.237
"can justly claim authority
unless it is based

00:47:26.237 --> 00:47:28.157
"on the will of the people."

00:47:29.090 --> 00:47:32.840
The Freedom Charter was an
expression of fierce opposition

00:47:32.840 --> 00:47:35.870
to the Apartheid regime
that had been established

00:47:35.870 --> 00:47:39.933
in South Africa and that
was to last until the 1990s.

00:47:40.960 --> 00:47:44.550
The Charter envisioned
a horizon of freedom

00:47:44.550 --> 00:47:49.053
amidst racial separation
and violent oppression.

00:47:50.620 --> 00:47:53.520
There is now a monument in Kliptown

00:47:53.520 --> 00:47:56.180
commemorating the Freedom Charter,

00:47:56.180 --> 00:48:00.310
complete with a swanky hotel with a bar

00:48:00.310 --> 00:48:02.660
which serves cocktails named after

00:48:02.660 --> 00:48:05.523
the main signatories
of the Freedom Charter.

00:48:07.214 --> 00:48:08.047
That, of course, is how freedom

00:48:08.047 --> 00:48:10.423
is bought and sold under capitalism.

00:48:12.390 --> 00:48:15.690
But what matters most to me was this.

00:48:15.690 --> 00:48:19.630
That less than half a mile from
the Freedom Charter monument

00:48:19.630 --> 00:48:23.070
were the shacks of the urban majority.

00:48:23.070 --> 00:48:26.760
Kliptown is a district in
Soweto, the most famous

00:48:26.760 --> 00:48:31.010
of the black townships created
by the Apartheid regime

00:48:31.010 --> 00:48:34.673
to quarantine and manage
black and colored labor.

00:48:35.610 --> 00:48:38.630
Today, decades after the end of Apartheid,

00:48:38.630 --> 00:48:40.143
the shacks remain.

00:48:41.030 --> 00:48:43.293
We were given the tour by Robert,

00:48:44.224 --> 00:48:48.500
who diligently keeps a
notebook of all visitors

00:48:48.500 --> 00:48:53.500
and generously tells the
story of each humiliation,

00:48:53.810 --> 00:48:56.793
each deprivation, each eviction.

00:48:58.300 --> 00:49:02.830
I, like some of you in this
room, came of political age

00:49:02.830 --> 00:49:05.820
during the anti-Apartheid movement.

00:49:05.820 --> 00:49:10.740
That struggle defined my
generation and ideas of freedom.

00:49:10.740 --> 00:49:13.093
This is from the Mandela House in Soweto.

00:49:14.430 --> 00:49:17.950
When Apartheid ended,
it seemed that the dream

00:49:17.950 --> 00:49:21.170
of freedom movements,
from anti-colonialism

00:49:21.170 --> 00:49:23.573
to civil rights, had been fulfilled.

00:49:24.600 --> 00:49:28.300
But the shacks of Kliptown
tell us otherwise.

00:49:28.300 --> 00:49:31.700
Invisible in the shadow
of Freedom Monument,

00:49:31.700 --> 00:49:35.860
they remind us that there
is urgent work to be done

00:49:35.860 --> 00:49:37.343
in all our cities.

00:49:39.030 --> 00:49:41.720
The shacks of Kliptown are an example

00:49:41.720 --> 00:49:45.560
of what Ruth Wilson Gilmore, a geographer

00:49:45.560 --> 00:49:49.670
and key proponent of abolitionist
thought and practice,

00:49:49.670 --> 00:49:52.430
has called forgotten places.

00:49:52.430 --> 00:49:54.710
The title of my brief
remarks this evening,

00:49:54.710 --> 00:49:58.880
Freedom is a Place, is also
borrowed from Ruthie Gilmore.

00:49:58.880 --> 00:50:02.720
Forgotten places, she
notes, have been shaped

00:50:02.720 --> 00:50:05.193
to organize abandonment.

00:50:06.150 --> 00:50:08.780
They have been red-lined, marginalized,

00:50:08.780 --> 00:50:12.950
contained, erased through state policies.

00:50:12.950 --> 00:50:16.673
In other words, abandonment
is actively produced.

00:50:17.847 --> 00:50:19.350
Much of my scholarship has been about

00:50:19.350 --> 00:50:22.003
such forms of state violence.

00:50:23.270 --> 00:50:27.360
For example, I study how
cities around the world,

00:50:27.360 --> 00:50:31.530
Mumbai, Rio de Janeiro,
Jakarta, Shanghai, Dubai,

00:50:31.530 --> 00:50:33.873
aspire to be world-class.

00:50:35.258 --> 00:50:37.730
Glittering assemblages of global capital

00:50:37.730 --> 00:50:39.353
and extravagant construction.

00:50:40.870 --> 00:50:45.257
But the urban majority of
these world-class cities

00:50:45.257 --> 00:50:48.040
`are slum dwellers, shack dwellers,

00:50:48.040 --> 00:50:50.823
migrant workers, day laborers.

00:50:51.660 --> 00:50:54.690
The paradox of the world-class city

00:50:54.690 --> 00:50:58.300
is that it expels from its very premises

00:50:58.300 --> 00:51:01.170
those who build and service it,

00:51:01.170 --> 00:51:04.260
those who raise its
children, cook its meals

00:51:04.260 --> 00:51:06.683
clean its villas and penthouses.

00:51:08.160 --> 00:51:12.230
So you see here satellite
images of Pushpa,

00:51:12.230 --> 00:51:14.740
a community on the banks
of the river Yamuna

00:51:14.740 --> 00:51:17.610
in the city of Delhi,
the capital of India.

00:51:17.610 --> 00:51:20.990
A community of 150,000 residents,

00:51:20.990 --> 00:51:24.250
it was in existence for about 39 years,

00:51:24.250 --> 00:51:27.560
cleared in the blink of an eye
for the Commonwealth Games,

00:51:27.560 --> 00:51:31.060
which Delhi hosted in 2010.

00:51:31.060 --> 00:51:33.800
I can give you countless examples

00:51:33.800 --> 00:51:36.720
of such evictions, of such erasure.

00:51:38.373 --> 00:51:40.733
This is necropolitics,
the politics of death,

00:51:42.000 --> 00:51:47.000
of the annihilation of space,
of the refusal to let live,

00:51:47.360 --> 00:51:50.103
the refusal to let exist.

00:51:50.940 --> 00:51:54.180
And yet, as Ruthie Gilmore reminds us,

00:51:54.180 --> 00:51:57.910
it is in the forgotten
places that we can find

00:51:57.910 --> 00:52:01.453
what she calls the seeds
of grassroots planning.

00:52:02.490 --> 00:52:05.230
The demands of such grassroots planning

00:52:05.230 --> 00:52:08.350
are not just about the
right to be in the city,

00:52:08.350 --> 00:52:11.360
the right to shelter, the right to water,

00:52:11.360 --> 00:52:14.523
they are above all about freedom.

00:52:16.460 --> 00:52:19.570
I was reminded of this when
I arrived in Los Angeles

00:52:19.570 --> 00:52:23.370
three years ago from
Berkeley, and had the task

00:52:23.370 --> 00:52:27.440
of establishing the Institute
on Inequality and Democracy

00:52:27.440 --> 00:52:29.383
here at UCLA Luskin.

00:52:30.220 --> 00:52:33.630
The Institute has benefited
from many teachers,

00:52:33.630 --> 00:52:35.163
but two were crucial.

00:52:36.050 --> 00:52:40.320
Robin D.G. Kelley's
pathbreaking book Freedom Dreams

00:52:40.320 --> 00:52:44.450
situated our effort to
advance housing justice,

00:52:44.450 --> 00:52:49.450
decarceration, desk disobedience,
educational reparations

00:52:49.540 --> 00:52:51.900
in the black radical tradition,

00:52:51.900 --> 00:52:54.743
and its commitment to abolition democracy.

00:52:56.000 --> 00:52:57.720
And our second teacher,

00:52:57.720 --> 00:53:02.260
the Los Angeles Community
Action Network, LA CAN,

00:53:02.260 --> 00:53:05.380
which has fought for poor
and homeless Angelenos

00:53:05.380 --> 00:53:08.350
for several decades now, from its location

00:53:08.350 --> 00:53:09.953
in the heart of Skid Row.

00:53:10.830 --> 00:53:14.223
LA CAN urged us as well
to think about freedom.

00:53:15.092 --> 00:53:16.550
For those of you on Twitter,

00:53:16.550 --> 00:53:20.633
their hashtag is quite
straightforward, Let's Get Free.

00:53:23.050 --> 00:53:27.040
Such freedom dreams are global in scope.

00:53:27.040 --> 00:53:29.930
They connect police
violence in the inner city

00:53:29.930 --> 00:53:34.930
of Los Angeles to that of the
favelas in Rio de Janeiro.

00:53:35.100 --> 00:53:38.550
They conceptualize, as did
the Black Panthers in Oakland,

00:53:38.550 --> 00:53:41.010
and Fanon in the context of the

00:53:41.010 --> 00:53:43.490
Algerian Independence Movement,

00:53:43.490 --> 00:53:48.370
a revolutionary humanism
that sees ghetto and colony

00:53:48.370 --> 00:53:53.230
as part of a world system of
colonialism and imperialism,

00:53:53.230 --> 00:53:56.783
and it insists on crafting liberation

00:53:56.783 --> 00:53:59.593
through such global interconnections.

00:54:01.070 --> 00:54:04.280
My own interest in homelessness, evictions

00:54:04.280 --> 00:54:08.430
and housing precarity in
the United States was shaped

00:54:08.430 --> 00:54:12.450
by an encounter many years
ago in Kolkata, India,

00:54:12.450 --> 00:54:14.920
the city in which I grew up and which was

00:54:14.920 --> 00:54:18.503
the subject of my doctoral
dissertation and first book.

00:54:19.440 --> 00:54:23.060
My research on gendered
poverty and urban displacement

00:54:23.060 --> 00:54:26.500
entails ethnographic
engagement with some of

00:54:26.500 --> 00:54:29.850
the poorest communities I will ever know.

00:54:29.850 --> 00:54:34.540
Those squatting in the
liminal spaces of the city

00:54:34.540 --> 00:54:38.273
with a tenuous hold on
livelihood and shelter.

00:54:40.170 --> 00:54:44.930
It was there that one day, a
young man called Ranjin decided

00:54:44.930 --> 00:54:49.570
that it was time for him
to ask me some questions,

00:54:49.570 --> 00:54:53.930
after having put up for about
a year with my questions

00:54:53.930 --> 00:54:57.570
and he wanted to ask me
questions about America,

00:54:57.570 --> 00:54:59.840
the richest country in the world.

00:54:59.840 --> 00:55:02.203
He asked, among other
things, the following.

00:55:03.107 --> 00:55:05.377
"Are there people like us there?

00:55:05.377 --> 00:55:07.977
"I've heard that there are
lots of homeless in America

00:55:07.977 --> 00:55:10.137
"How can that be the case?

00:55:10.137 --> 00:55:12.237
"Why doesn't the government
simply allow them

00:55:12.237 --> 00:55:16.833
:to take over vacant lands
like we have, to build homes?

00:55:17.767 --> 00:55:21.217
"Aren't they citizens,
don't they have rights?"

00:55:22.200 --> 00:55:26.230
In the face of all my
explanations, Ranjin insisted,

00:55:26.230 --> 00:55:29.773
if one's a citizen, one can't be homeless.

00:55:30.690 --> 00:55:32.930
Ranjin's question has stayed with me

00:55:32.930 --> 00:55:37.520
because it not only exposes
the lie of American prosperity

00:55:37.520 --> 00:55:40.980
but also the lie of liberal democracy,

00:55:40.980 --> 00:55:42.983
and its assumptions of freedom.

00:55:44.220 --> 00:55:46.530
So it is with Ranjin's question in mind

00:55:46.530 --> 00:55:49.970
that I want to in closing
turn to Los Angeles

00:55:49.970 --> 00:55:53.340
and provide you with a
glimpse of some of the issues

00:55:53.340 --> 00:55:56.780
that animate my current research.

00:55:56.780 --> 00:56:00.070
In the United States, the
unfinished project of freedom

00:56:00.070 --> 00:56:03.963
is closely linked to
questions of space and place.

00:56:05.550 --> 00:56:08.630
The sociologist Douglas
Massey, who co-authored

00:56:08.630 --> 00:56:12.510
a vitally important book
titled American Apartheid,

00:56:12.510 --> 00:56:17.510
reminds us that residential
segregation is the linchpin

00:56:18.180 --> 00:56:22.120
of racial stratification
in the United States.

00:56:22.120 --> 00:56:26.740
The history of urban planning
in 20th century America

00:56:26.740 --> 00:56:29.370
is the story of how this segregation

00:56:29.370 --> 00:56:32.020
was produced and maintained.

00:56:32.020 --> 00:56:35.400
Suburban expansion went hand in hand

00:56:35.400 --> 00:56:39.700
with the redlining of black
and brown communities.

00:56:39.700 --> 00:56:42.120
Here is one of the many redlining maps

00:56:42.120 --> 00:56:44.200
produced by federal government agency

00:56:44.200 --> 00:56:46.460
the Homeowners Loan Corporation,

00:56:46.460 --> 00:56:49.860
in the 1930s for Los Angeles.

00:56:49.860 --> 00:56:53.410
Consider this map alongside this one,

00:56:53.410 --> 00:56:57.990
of environmental racism, and
you will begin to understand

00:56:57.990 --> 00:57:02.727
why Ruthie Gilmore reminds
us that racism is, I quote,

00:57:02.727 --> 00:57:07.547
"the state-sanctioned production
of group differentiated

00:57:07.547 --> 00:57:10.657
"vulnerability to premature death."

00:57:12.350 --> 00:57:16.570
Today, the places once inhabited
by redlined communities

00:57:16.570 --> 00:57:19.550
are the frontiers of gentrification.

00:57:19.550 --> 00:57:22.877
South Los Angeles, Boyle Heights.

00:57:22.877 --> 00:57:25.650
Working class communities of color

00:57:25.650 --> 00:57:29.020
are being pushed to the
far edges of urban life,

00:57:29.020 --> 00:57:32.700
to the inland empire, to Antelope Valley.

00:57:32.700 --> 00:57:35.620
They're being pushed there
not only by high rent

00:57:35.620 --> 00:57:39.730
but also through a whole
set of municipal ordinances

00:57:39.730 --> 00:57:42.760
that criminalize poverty and in particular

00:57:42.760 --> 00:57:46.253
criminalize low-income rental households.

00:57:47.510 --> 00:57:49.960
So did you know that in
the city of Los Angeles

00:57:49.960 --> 00:57:52.643
it is now illegal to live in your car?

00:57:54.300 --> 00:57:57.370
Did you that if you're
a tenant in a building

00:57:57.370 --> 00:58:00.790
governed by a nuisance
abatement ordinance,

00:58:00.790 --> 00:58:05.420
you might be evicted
if you have called 911

00:58:05.420 --> 00:58:08.003
more than once during the year.

00:58:09.510 --> 00:58:12.810
This is not market-driven displacement.

00:58:12.810 --> 00:58:16.440
I call it racial
banishment, and it is part

00:58:16.440 --> 00:58:19.310
of the long history of the forced removal

00:58:19.310 --> 00:58:22.160
of people of color, from settler colonial

00:58:22.160 --> 00:58:25.900
occupation and slavery to urban renewal

00:58:25.900 --> 00:58:28.463
to today's militarized borders.

00:58:29.565 --> 00:58:32.800
But it in the face of
such racial banishments

00:58:32.800 --> 00:58:36.580
that poor people's movements
in cities such as Los Angeles

00:58:36.580 --> 00:58:38.723
are insisting on freedom.

00:58:39.720 --> 00:58:42.100
In exactly two weeks from now,

00:58:42.100 --> 00:58:45.403
California will vote on Proposition 10,

00:58:46.260 --> 00:58:49.100
which if it passes, will repeal

00:58:49.100 --> 00:58:53.040
statewide restrictions on rent control.

00:58:53.040 --> 00:58:56.190
Tenants have been organizing
to build renter power

00:58:56.190 --> 00:59:00.863
and to remind us that the
rent is too damn high.

00:59:02.090 --> 00:59:06.740
Communities from Los Angeles
and South LA to Santa Ana

00:59:06.740 --> 00:59:09.570
are creating community land trusts

00:59:09.570 --> 00:59:13.993
and reactivating lost
histories of collectivism.

00:59:14.880 --> 00:59:18.050
In Boyle Heights, social
movements are fighting

00:59:18.050 --> 00:59:22.460
gentrification and displacement,
including the influx

00:59:22.460 --> 00:59:25.823
of hipster coffee shops and art galleries.

00:59:26.700 --> 00:59:29.483
In the words of LA CAN, let's get free.

00:59:30.640 --> 00:59:34.280
My work as a scholar,
and the work we try to do

00:59:34.280 --> 00:59:37.230
at the Institute on
Inequality and Democracy

00:59:37.230 --> 00:59:41.430
proceeds from a commitment
to abolition democracy.

00:59:41.430 --> 00:59:43.440
By abolition, I do not simply mean

00:59:43.440 --> 00:59:46.680
the end of the prison-industrial complex.

00:59:46.680 --> 00:59:51.680
I mean abolition as redistribution,
reparation, revolution

00:59:52.490 --> 00:59:56.830
and above all, what W.E.B. DuBois in 1935

00:59:56.830 --> 01:00:00.230
described as black reconstruction.

01:00:00.230 --> 01:00:03.540
A new state, a new public imagination,

01:00:03.540 --> 01:00:06.480
built through the uprising of those

01:00:06.480 --> 01:00:08.610
who have been denied freedom,

01:00:08.610 --> 01:00:11.740
those who have been denied personhood.

01:00:11.740 --> 01:00:15.450
This is, as post-colonial
theorist Paul Gilroy notes,

01:00:15.450 --> 01:00:18.660
history from the slave's standpoint.

01:00:18.660 --> 01:00:23.053
This is freedom, from the
standpoint of forgotten places.

01:00:25.100 --> 01:00:29.250
My closing point is this,
that as we do this work,

01:00:29.250 --> 01:00:32.500
there is no obvious solidarity

01:00:32.500 --> 01:00:36.053
between academia and banished communities.

01:00:36.950 --> 01:00:41.950
Our public university itself
stands on occupied land,

01:00:42.020 --> 01:00:46.073
land expropriated from
indigenous communities.

01:00:46.920 --> 01:00:50.320
We, scholars of freedom, are embedded

01:00:50.320 --> 01:00:53.623
in the institutions of racial capitalism,

01:00:54.620 --> 01:00:56.360
and so I leave you with a thought

01:00:56.360 --> 01:00:58.633
that if we, the public universities,

01:00:59.715 --> 01:01:02.580
are to participate in freedom dreams,

01:01:02.580 --> 01:01:07.580
then we also have to insist on
decolonizing the universities

01:01:07.740 --> 01:01:10.370
and the decolonization of knowledge,

01:01:10.370 --> 01:01:13.730
on a reconstruction of our canon,

01:01:13.730 --> 01:01:17.960
on a reckoning with who
gets to be at the university

01:01:17.960 --> 01:01:19.653
and on what terms.

01:01:20.870 --> 01:01:24.470
For the students in the
class, you might recall

01:01:24.470 --> 01:01:28.860
