I asked you to consider

01:01:28.860 --> 01:01:33.310
was to listen to a bit of
hip-hop, and I hope you did that.

01:01:33.310 --> 01:01:34.400
Yes?

01:01:34.400 --> 01:01:38.650
I asked you to listen to a
song by the rapper J. Cole,

01:01:38.650 --> 01:01:42.200
a song called "Neighbors,"
which speaks to the theme

01:01:42.200 --> 01:01:45.503
of racial banishment and
the limits of integration.

01:01:46.340 --> 01:01:50.360
J. Cole belongs to a tradition
of hip-hop that foregrants

01:01:50.360 --> 01:01:54.000
what Michelle Alexander has
called the new Jim Crow,

01:01:54.000 --> 01:01:56.850
the forms of carcerality
and criminalization

01:01:56.850 --> 01:02:00.883
that perpetuate racial
segregation in the United States.

01:02:01.840 --> 01:02:06.270
In his latest album,
K.O.D, J. Cole raps about

01:02:06.270 --> 01:02:10.670
knowledge and power, about
the curriculum that tricks us.

01:02:10.670 --> 01:02:13.757
He says, "One thing about the men

01:02:13.757 --> 01:02:17.067
"that's controlling the
pen that write history,

01:02:17.067 --> 01:02:20.327
"they always seem to
white out their sins."

01:02:21.450 --> 01:02:26.450
The dream of freedom means
changing who controls the pen.

01:02:26.810 --> 01:02:31.010
It means getting very
serious about urban histories

01:02:31.010 --> 01:02:35.890
and urban futures that
center forgotten places.

01:02:35.890 --> 01:02:37.003
Thank you.

