01:06:46.830 --> 01:06:51.560
that there's, even if
you're on the bottom,

01:06:51.560 --> 01:06:53.730
there's space to find creativity,

01:06:53.730 --> 01:06:56.930
and that may or may not
satisfy a desire for freedom

01:06:56.930 --> 01:07:01.130
but it's, I think it's something,
it's some sense of agency.

01:07:01.130 --> 01:07:02.563
That's more than nothing.

01:07:03.630 --> 01:07:06.834
- Well, if I could maybe jump in there,

01:07:06.834 --> 01:07:10.282
because I would say that you are enacting

01:07:10.282 --> 01:07:14.650
your artistic freedom in that
work, as well as creativity,

01:07:14.650 --> 01:07:16.520
in the way that you framed it initially,

01:07:16.520 --> 01:07:19.100
which is freedom within constraints

01:07:19.100 --> 01:07:21.640
that you yourself construct.

01:07:21.640 --> 01:07:24.590
Although they're not
entirely constructed by you,

01:07:24.590 --> 01:07:27.330
but they're chosen constraints,

01:07:27.330 --> 01:07:32.330
so within that work, even
if you take up a position

01:07:32.470 --> 01:07:37.470
that is constrained or
not necessarily in control

01:07:37.550 --> 01:07:42.550
or entirely free, it's
your own construction

01:07:43.480 --> 01:07:47.170
within your own sort of system,
your own artistic system

01:07:47.170 --> 01:07:52.170
which you yourself are
constructing within your, you know,

01:07:52.420 --> 01:07:57.123
freedom as an artist, so
that's how I would understand.

01:07:59.832 --> 01:08:01.810
- I think there's another
part which I didn't,

01:08:01.810 --> 01:08:04.290
there's another part of the
