01:09:45.880 --> 01:09:50.880
and optimistic call to think
about deliberative speech

01:09:53.430 --> 01:09:55.810
and the ways in which we
might be able to listen,

01:09:55.810 --> 01:09:58.530
even to that which is not spoken,

01:09:58.530 --> 01:10:01.553
and particularly in the context,
for example, of strikes,

01:10:03.300 --> 01:10:06.860
and Andrea ended with the
current historical conjunction

01:10:06.860 --> 01:10:11.860
which we find ourselves, and
the particular regime in place

01:10:14.130 --> 01:10:17.250
and the various assaults on the most basic

01:10:17.250 --> 01:10:21.740
of democratic freedoms,
and I'm wondering then

01:10:21.740 --> 01:10:26.340
what it means to think about,
and this is a rather obvious

01:10:26.340 --> 01:10:29.250
and perhaps cliched question,
about what it then means

01:10:29.250 --> 01:10:31.800
for us to think about
the freedom of speech

01:10:31.800 --> 01:10:35.000
and who is entitled to
the freedom of speech,

01:10:35.000 --> 01:10:39.940
but also what that means then
if we are to listen carefully

01:10:39.940 --> 01:10:42.440
and to speak with and
even listen to silence,

01:10:42.440 --> 01:10:43.740
since one thing, and I'm going to say this

01:10:43.740 --> 01:10:46.230
very bluntly and crudely,
it's one thing when it's

01:10:46.230 --> 01:10:49.230
striking workers with
whom we feel solidarity

01:10:49.230 --> 01:10:53.257
and we see as making
possible, as you note,

01:10:53.257 --> 01:10:56.720
our intellectual work, and it's another

01:10:56.720 --> 01:10:58.843
when it's right-wing nationalists.

01:11:00.480 --> 01:11:01.313
Or is it not?

01:11:04.840 --> 01:11:09.840
- [Seanna] Well, I think it's
really important to listen

01:11:12.530 --> 01:11:16.163
and not to think that listening
is a sign of agreement,

01:11:17.840 --> 01:11:20.470
but that we can't make progress together

01:11:22.077 --> 01:11:26.620
until we understand each
other, and that does involve

01:11:26.620 --> 01:11:30.453
trying to figure out why
people think what they do.

01:11:32.073 --> 01:11:37.073
So I do think it includes listening to

01:11:37.610 --> 01:11:42.610
right-wing nationalists and
also responding to them directly

01:11:42.810 --> 01:11:47.810
and candidly, but yeah, I
am gonna take that view.

01:11:52.292 --> 01:11:53.300
- I also think that this
relates to the question

01:11:53.300 --> 01:11:56.860
that Brett just asked me,
because in the sort of

01:11:56.860 --> 01:11:59.205
the communities that I was talking about,

01:11:59.205 --> 01:12:00.540
so if you talk about
banishment communities

01:12:00.540 --> 01:12:02.440
that have faced organized abandonment,

01:12:05.415 --> 01:12:09.010
they would argue that certain
forms of speech and action

01:12:09.010 --> 01:12:12.750
have sought to erase
them, as we have seen with

01:12:12.750 --> 01:12:17.293
the erasure of transgender
identity in people, personhood.

01:12:18.210 --> 01:12:20.350
Right, so this is the
dispossession not only of lands

01:12:20.350 --> 01:12:24.090
in cities, but this is the
dispossession of personhood.

01:12:24.090 --> 01:12:26.670
It's a sort of violence, it's an erasure

01:12:26.670 --> 01:12:29.683
of the very grounds of existence.

01:12:30.850 --> 01:12:35.450
So I'm trying to figure out what listening

01:12:35.450 --> 01:12:39.970
in those contexts means,
given this sort of

01:12:39.970 --> 01:12:43.970
profound inequality, which
to me is at the very core

01:12:43.970 --> 01:12:47.710
of liberal democracy, and
so how then do we listen

01:12:47.710 --> 01:12:50.690
or particularly, if the
means of communication

01:12:50.690 --> 01:12:53.506
which in this case we might call the media

01:12:53.506 --> 01:12:58.330
in the United States, are
also thoroughly eroded,

01:12:58.330 --> 01:13:02.160
how then, what are the spheres
within which we listen,

01:13:02.160 --> 01:13:05.160
what are the means through which
we might be able to listen?

01:13:07.090 --> 01:13:12.090
- [Seanna] Well, I agree with
you that the corporate control

01:13:12.090 --> 01:13:17.090
of the media, as well as the
normalization of positions

01:13:18.730 --> 01:13:21.400
that are associated with
the erasure of communities

01:13:21.400 --> 01:13:26.400
is appalling, and an aspect
of changing that is to

01:13:26.649 --> 01:13:30.393
engage in a variety of forms
of anti-trust of the media,

01:13:31.230 --> 01:13:32.780
to look at greater sources.

01:13:32.780 --> 01:13:35.900
I encourage everyone to
read different newspapers

01:13:35.900 --> 01:13:37.913
than the ones they normally read.

01:13:38.830 --> 01:13:42.010
Not just because there are lots of stories

01:13:42.010 --> 01:13:44.810
that are not being told, but because

01:13:44.810 --> 01:13:47.360
you need to understand what
other people are thinking

01:13:47.360 --> 01:13:51.590
and reading and consuming,
and then asking people,

01:13:51.590 --> 01:13:53.550
what stories do you
think aren't being told?

01:13:53.550 --> 01:13:54.760
Why aren't they being told?

01:13:54.760 --> 01:13:57.330
Why don't you know the
answers to that question?

01:13:57.330 --> 01:13:59.880
Why didn't you know
before you came tonight

01:13:59.880 --> 01:14:02.560
that it's become illegal
to live in your car?

01:14:02.560 --> 01:14:04.550
How is that not something that was on

01:14:04.550 --> 01:14:06.393
the front page of the LA Times?

01:14:07.610 --> 01:14:12.380
I think starting, everyone
demanding to know these things

01:14:12.380 --> 01:14:14.700
and engaging in legal reforms

01:14:14.700 --> 01:14:17.100
is part of the way I would
try to approach that.

01:14:24.160 --> 01:14:26.100
- One of the points very much touched on,

01:14:26.100 --> 01:14:29.870
really in different ways
across the four presentations

01:14:29.870 --> 01:14:34.710
is almost a plea for forms of agency.

01:14:34.710 --> 01:14:36.850
Listening, in fact, can be thought of

01:14:36.850 --> 01:14:39.910
as a form of agency, in its own way,

01:14:39.910 --> 01:14:42.420
That action as we know it might fit in

01:14:42.420 --> 01:14:44.380
how we operate within discipline,

01:14:44.380 --> 01:14:47.040
in relation to contemporary technologies,

01:14:47.040 --> 01:14:50.810
in a complex urban space
like a global city,

01:14:50.810 --> 01:14:53.300
and that's one of the things
that's being touched on

01:14:53.300 --> 01:14:55.940
in the design of a course
like that, like this one,

01:14:55.940 --> 01:14:58.240
to think of a member of an audience

01:14:58.240 --> 01:15:03.240
as a form of agency and
not simply a setting

01:15:03.890 --> 01:15:06.330
for a spectacle or an event to play out,

01:15:06.330 --> 01:15:09.400
to be simply received by
members of that community,

01:15:09.400 --> 01:15:11.800
but that to come together in a room

01:15:11.800 --> 01:15:16.050
is a kind of agency that allows
for the asking of questions

01:15:16.050 --> 01:15:18.670
in addition to whatever one
might be put on the stage

01:15:18.670 --> 01:15:20.460
to kick off a larger conversation.

01:15:20.460 --> 01:15:22.300
I use that all as a little segue

01:15:23.260 --> 01:15:24.840
to what I hope has taken place

01:15:24.840 --> 01:15:26.490
while the conversation has begun here,

01:15:26.490 --> 01:15:29.070
which is we've got a couple of microphones

01:15:29.070 --> 01:15:32.350
that ought to be moving
around the room already.

01:15:32.350 --> 01:15:34.030
I asked you to take a minute or two

01:15:34.030 --> 01:15:36.430
to rehearse a couple of questions,

01:15:36.430 --> 01:15:39.200
or to comment to one another,
your neighbors nearby,

01:15:39.200 --> 01:15:41.510
about things that you've seen and heard.

01:15:41.510 --> 01:15:42.950
I'm gonna ask the students especially

01:15:42.950 --> 01:15:44.400
to kick off the kind of questions

01:15:44.400 --> 01:15:46.500
that can carry the conversation forward.

01:15:46.500 --> 01:15:47.930
Please.

01:15:47.930 --> 01:15:50.910
- [Student] So my question's
