01:16:22.680 --> 01:16:23.670
- [Student] So if we believe we're free,

01:16:23.670 --> 01:16:26.870
does it actually confine
us and not allow us to see

01:16:26.870 --> 01:16:29.740
how we impose surveillance on ourselves

01:16:29.740 --> 01:16:32.650
and not allow us to see how
we internalize and regurgitate

01:16:32.650 --> 01:16:35.883
capitalism and other
oppressive institutions?

01:16:38.340 --> 01:16:40.413
- That was easier to
hear, the second version.

01:16:43.804 --> 01:16:46.209
- I could still se a
repetition of the question.

01:16:46.209 --> 01:16:48.785
I am kind of new so it's really difficult,

01:16:48.785 --> 01:16:50.435
but you guys might have heard it.

01:16:52.670 --> 01:16:53.970
- Freedom in the context of

01:16:53.970 --> 01:16:56.050
being embedded in capitalism, right?

01:16:56.050 --> 01:16:58.280
How can we think of ourselves as free

01:16:58.280 --> 01:17:01.360
if we are very much a part of
these systems of capitalism?

01:17:01.360 --> 01:17:02.520
Is that the question?

01:17:02.520 --> 01:17:05.350
I'm sorry to oversimplify it.

01:17:05.350 --> 01:17:07.063
All right, okay.

01:17:11.450 --> 01:17:13.890
- I'll start by saying a
couple of standard things.

01:17:13.890 --> 01:17:16.820
None of us will be free
until all of us are free.

01:17:16.820 --> 01:17:19.670
We're not gonna experience full freedom

01:17:19.670 --> 01:17:24.670
until everyone is correctly
empowered to live their lives,

01:17:25.140 --> 01:17:28.595
but we can appreciate a part of freedom

01:17:28.595 --> 01:17:33.595
by exercising our imagination
and our critical thinking,

01:17:34.206 --> 01:17:35.039
to imagine what it would be like

01:17:35.039 --> 01:17:36.883
to live with each other in a better way.

01:17:41.112 --> 01:17:42.480
- So I would follow on
that, so one of the concepts

01:17:42.480 --> 01:17:45.580
I like using in my work
is I try to think about

01:17:45.580 --> 01:17:49.180
whether abolitionist
urban planning is possible

01:17:49.180 --> 01:17:51.123
and whether it's possible to be at

01:17:51.123 --> 01:17:53.520
a public university, which
see as an institution

01:17:53.520 --> 01:17:56.080
of racial capitalism,
and is it possible for us

01:17:56.080 --> 01:17:58.200
to advance the work of social justice?

01:17:58.200 --> 01:18:00.960
It's a concept that comes
both from post-colonial theory

01:18:00.960 --> 01:18:03.920
and from black studies,
is the idea of doubleness,

01:18:03.920 --> 01:18:06.810
that we are on the one
hand cogs in the machine,

01:18:06.810 --> 01:18:10.223
and yet we have the
possibilities of insurgency.

01:18:11.210 --> 01:18:14.410
That we are part of the
system and yet we have

01:18:14.410 --> 01:18:19.016
the ability to say no, right,
to these structures of power,

01:18:19.016 --> 01:18:23.360
and that is not as simple
as individual agency.

01:18:23.360 --> 01:18:26.020
To me this has to do with projects

01:18:26.020 --> 01:18:30.020
of collaboration and solidarity
with the freedom struggles

01:18:30.020 --> 01:18:32.980
that we enlist ourselves
in and that we insist on

01:18:32.980 --> 01:18:35.720
becoming a part of, and on thinking about

01:18:35.720 --> 01:18:38.010
how the very terrain of disciplines

01:18:38.010 --> 01:18:40.240
has been shaped by these struggles

01:18:40.240 --> 01:18:43.148
and therefore when we belong,
we're not just belonging,

01:18:43.148 --> 01:18:46.292
as Andrea's presentation made it clear,

01:18:46.292 --> 01:18:48.807
to a generic notion of capitalism

01:18:48.807 --> 01:18:53.410
but to the ways in which
our very fields of inquiry

01:18:53.410 --> 01:18:56.910
have been shaped by
this political economy,

01:18:56.910 --> 01:19:00.070
so I'm very interested in the
ways in which I see myself

01:19:00.070 --> 01:19:04.787
not as innocent, but very
much a part of these systems,

01:19:04.787 --> 01:19:08.290
but yet from within
it, from the very heart

01:19:08.290 --> 01:19:11.080
of imperial power or racial capitalism,

01:19:11.080 --> 01:19:12.960
being able to not only advance a critique,

01:19:12.960 --> 01:19:16.713
but think about imaginations
and practices of liberation.

01:19:18.460 --> 01:19:20.410
But that's, as I said, for me personally,

01:19:20.410 --> 01:19:24.580
that comes through the
difficult and patient work

01:19:24.580 --> 01:19:29.580
of solidarity with what I
called forgotten places.

01:19:32.972 --> 01:19:35.970
- So my tradition of practice
is institutional critique,

01:19:35.970 --> 01:19:40.490
which I understand as a
kind of critically reflexive

01:19:40.490 --> 01:19:44.000
critique of one's own
interests and investments

01:19:44.000 --> 01:19:46.560
and privileges in the specific fields

01:19:46.560 --> 01:19:48.763
and institutions of one's activity,

01:19:49.936 --> 01:19:52.210
and the way that I think
about the possibility of that,

01:19:52.210 --> 01:19:54.860
partly is the possibility that's rooted in

01:19:54.860 --> 01:19:57.670
always what's a partial
freedom, a relative freedom,

01:19:57.670 --> 01:20:02.670
a relative autonomy, of one
field relative to another field,

01:20:06.820 --> 01:20:09.920
of a particular set of practices or values

01:20:09.920 --> 01:20:14.920
or discourses or
institutions as they develop

01:20:18.950 --> 01:20:20.860
in relationship to other fields,

01:20:20.860 --> 01:20:25.860
so that's why I went down
that road in my presentation.

01:20:35.491 --> 01:20:37.400
Working with the notion
of relative autonomy

01:20:37.400 --> 01:20:39.220
and applying it to freedom...

01:20:45.490 --> 01:20:48.163
Within the framework of capitalism, yeah.

01:20:52.437 --> 01:20:55.990
(audience laughing quietly)

01:20:55.990 --> 01:20:57.543
How do I do that exactly?

01:21:01.580 --> 01:21:05.180
You know, to the extent that we're up here

01:21:05.180 --> 01:21:08.903
with our particular
discourses abour freedom,

01:21:08.903 --> 01:21:13.310
whether they're disciplinary
or politically rooted,

01:21:13.310 --> 01:21:16.650
we're up here because we're enabled by

01:21:16.650 --> 01:21:20.450
the conditions and traditions
of this institution

01:21:20.450 --> 01:21:24.230
and our individual fields,
our particular field,

01:21:24.230 --> 01:21:27.073
to develop and articulate those critiques.

01:21:28.160 --> 01:21:31.300
And no, it's not a total freedom,

01:21:31.300 --> 01:21:35.180
it's a relative freedom
within a set of constraints

01:21:35.180 --> 01:21:39.820
that we have to challenge
ourselves to work within, to test,

01:21:41.100 --> 01:21:46.100
to reproduce, to defend to the
greatest extent that we can.

01:21:49.150 --> 01:21:54.150
From my perspective, in an
embedded, sort of site-specific

01:21:54.770 --> 01:21:59.750
and also reflexive way,
because as sort of pressing

01:22:01.256 --> 01:22:06.256
and terrifying the threats
from outside of our fields

01:22:09.540 --> 01:22:14.540
and institutions are, I
think there's threats...

01:22:17.600 --> 01:22:21.230
The threats from within our institutions

01:22:21.230 --> 01:22:25.979
that weaken our institutions
and make them vulnerable

01:22:25.979 --> 01:22:30.979
to attacks from white supremacists,

01:22:34.460 --> 01:22:39.460
that make them vulnerable
to corruption by plutocrats,

01:22:42.460 --> 01:22:47.460
are in fact, the threats that
we have the power to engage

01:22:48.870 --> 01:22:51.343
most directly and most effectively.

01:22:54.040 --> 01:22:57.900
- Yeah, I think, if we're
talking about freedom

01:22:57.900 --> 01:22:59.420
in the sense of free will, even if you can

01:22:59.420 --> 01:23:03.610
take off capitalism or
you take off a particular

01:23:03.610 --> 01:23:05.433
government or political structure,

01:23:06.503 --> 01:23:08.030
just the expectations that we have

01:23:08.030 --> 01:23:10.107
of each other socially, limit us.

01:23:11.160 --> 01:23:12.960
I'm not rolling on the ground right now,

01:23:12.960 --> 01:23:15.403
I'm sitting in a chair
just like everyone else.

01:23:16.890 --> 01:23:20.350
So I think maybe it's more
helpful to think about

01:23:20.350 --> 01:23:23.430
agency or as Andrea
said, what can we change?

01:23:23.430 --> 01:23:27.550
So maybe, yes, you're not free
of the system of capitalism,

01:23:27.550 --> 01:23:30.180
you're not free of the
inequalities that we have

01:23:30.180 --> 01:23:32.310
all around us, but if you
can start to see them,

01:23:32.310 --> 01:23:35.460
then you can also start to
see, what can you change?

01:23:35.460 --> 01:23:36.360
What can you do?

01:23:36.360 --> 01:23:39.773
So what action is there
some freedom to maneuver?

01:23:43.560 --> 01:23:45.795
- Terrific, you right here.

01:23:45.795 --> 01:23:47.697
- [Student] Thank you.

01:23:47.697 --> 01:23:49.240
I just wanna say, I love public education.

01:23:49.240 --> 01:23:53.023
Thank you ladies for
fortifying it in California.

01:23:54.430 --> 01:23:56.420
So I'm a two-time Bruin, went to LA USD

01:23:56.420 --> 01:23:58.490
and I'm a teacher in LA USD now,

01:23:58.490 --> 01:24:01.430
so our teachers are heading into a strike

01:24:01.430 --> 01:24:03.483
with more and more momentum each week,

01:24:04.799 --> 01:24:06.990
and we're taking issue
with the encroachment

01:24:06.990 --> 01:24:11.990
of big business in K-12 public
education, specifically.

01:24:15.270 --> 01:24:18.500
It seems incompatible,
you have big business

01:24:18.500 --> 01:24:21.410
where the primary principle
is greed over everything else,

01:24:21.410 --> 01:24:26.410
and public education where
it's human development

01:24:26.410 --> 01:24:30.843
before anything else, so let me ask you,

01:24:32.410 --> 01:24:34.880
given this encroachment of big business

01:24:34.880 --> 01:24:39.880
in K-12 public education,
what are the links between

01:24:40.200 --> 01:24:45.200
public education and
freedom in a democracy?

01:24:47.560 --> 01:24:49.460
And I also want to say, Professor Roy,

01:24:50.350 --> 01:24:52.870
as I was listening to you, I
couldn't help but reminisce

01:24:52.870 --> 01:24:56.000
on Professor Jacqueline
Leavitt, rest in peace.

01:24:56.000 --> 01:24:57.700
She had a tremendous impact on me,

01:24:58.784 --> 01:25:00.384
and you two, Professor Shiffrin.

01:25:01.780 --> 01:25:03.838
You guys understand my
question, or should I...

01:25:03.838 --> 01:25:04.671
- I got your question.

01:25:04.671 --> 01:25:05.504
- We got it.

01:25:05.504 --> 01:25:07.000
- I think they got it.

01:25:07.000 --> 01:25:07.833
- Thank you.

01:25:10.910 --> 01:25:12.140
- [Seanna] I'll go first again.

01:25:12.140 --> 01:25:12.973
- Yes.

01:25:14.090 --> 01:25:18.400
- [Seanna] You asked
about what we think about

01:25:18.400 --> 01:25:20.400
the relationship between public education

01:25:20.400 --> 01:25:22.970
and democratic freedom.

01:25:22.970 --> 01:25:24.810
I won't speak for everyone
else, but I'll say

01:25:24.810 --> 01:25:27.630
that I think it is one
of the most important

01:25:27.630 --> 01:25:30.700
foundational aspects of a democracy,

01:25:30.700 --> 01:25:34.610
that we fund all of our
citizens as children

01:25:34.610 --> 01:25:39.610
and all residents as
children, to be together,

01:25:41.080 --> 01:25:44.260
to be together and to learn together.

01:25:44.260 --> 01:25:46.770
And the reason why
that's vitally important

01:25:46.770 --> 01:25:50.800
is because we're then going
to try to cooperate together

01:25:50.800 --> 01:25:53.060
and govern together.

01:25:53.060 --> 01:25:57.200
The whole point of a democracy is that you

01:25:58.684 --> 01:25:59.840
live with one another and
cooperate with one another

01:25:59.840 --> 01:26:02.430
and the ideal of public education

01:26:02.430 --> 01:26:07.430
is to introduce all different
kinds of people to each other

01:26:07.775 --> 01:26:10.650
and to give them new experiences

01:26:10.650 --> 01:26:12.580
that are different from the experiences

01:26:12.580 --> 01:26:14.820
that they get in their own homes.

01:26:14.820 --> 01:26:19.240
That is, to ask children to
learn how to cooperate with

01:26:19.240 --> 01:26:24.240
one another, just based on the
fact that they're residents.

01:26:25.573 --> 01:26:30.400
And so, I think that you can't
really have a vital democracy

01:26:30.400 --> 01:26:33.530
unless you have a vital
public education system

01:26:33.530 --> 01:26:35.480
that everyone is asked to be a part of,

01:26:36.500 --> 01:26:41.090
but it will only work, and
this relates to Ananya's work,

01:26:41.090 --> 01:26:45.440
if we don't allow residential
segregation to introduce

01:26:45.440 --> 01:26:49.500
the separation that public
education is supposed to solve,

01:26:49.500 --> 01:26:53.715
and I grew up in Los
Angeles and I was part of

01:26:53.715 --> 01:26:58.290
the desegregation
movement, and it is one of

01:26:58.290 --> 01:27:01.200
the best things that ever happened to me.

01:27:01.200 --> 01:27:03.950
Getting on a bus and meeting people from

01:27:03.950 --> 01:27:06.610
different neighborhoods
and different walks of life

01:27:06.610 --> 01:27:10.580
was the most important part
of my education as a person,

01:27:10.580 --> 01:27:13.700
and I think one of the
worst things that we did

01:27:13.700 --> 01:27:17.905
was to eliminate
desegregation in education

01:27:17.905 --> 01:27:21.613
and to fail to solve
residential segregation.

01:27:27.460 --> 01:27:28.293
- I agree.

01:27:29.312 --> 01:27:32.479
(audience applauding)

01:27:34.675 --> 01:27:35.760
- So I just wanted to build on that

01:27:35.760 --> 01:27:39.090
because defending and
fighting for, quite literally,

01:27:39.090 --> 01:27:41.930
the public university has been for me

01:27:41.930 --> 01:27:44.010
one of the most important
things I do in my career,

01:27:44.010 --> 01:27:46.590
so I was on the faculty at Berkeley

01:27:46.590 --> 01:27:49.580
when the massive tuition hikes happened,

01:27:49.580 --> 01:27:54.150
and we were quite literally
on strike, at the barricades

01:27:54.150 --> 01:27:56.630
in solidarity with students and workers

01:27:56.630 --> 01:28:00.113
as they occupied buildings on campus.

01:28:01.030 --> 01:28:04.610
And I think that those
uprisings were important

01:28:04.610 --> 01:28:07.840
because it made it clear
to the state legislature

01:28:07.840 --> 01:28:09.750
that we were not going to be defeated,

01:28:09.750 --> 01:28:13.510
that we were gonna fight
for higher public education,

01:28:13.510 --> 01:28:17.990
and I say this at the same
time as we were also fighting

01:28:17.990 --> 01:28:20.150
for the decolonization of the university.

01:28:20.150 --> 01:28:22.860
So we recognize precisely
that while we're defending

01:28:22.860 --> 01:28:25.920
public education, we have
to think about the ways

01:28:25.920 --> 01:28:29.400
in which residential
segregation then shapes

01:28:29.400 --> 01:28:31.560
the nature of public education.

01:28:31.560 --> 01:28:33.170
As we fight for the public university,

01:28:33.170 --> 01:28:35.994
we've got to think about who gets to be at

01:28:35.994 --> 01:28:37.550
the public university, and does this

01:28:37.550 --> 01:28:40.347
really look like the state of California?

01:28:40.347 --> 01:28:44.620
And if not, then how do we change that?

01:28:44.620 --> 01:28:47.100
But the point that,
the reason why I smiled

01:28:47.100 --> 01:28:49.420
when you asked that question, is because

01:28:49.420 --> 01:28:53.290
I ended by referring
to the work of DuBois,

01:28:53.290 --> 01:28:55.800
and his idea of black reconstruction

01:28:55.800 --> 01:28:58.870
and one of the most beautiful
passages in that book,

01:28:58.870 --> 01:29:03.870
written in 1935, is when
DuBois talks about schools,

01:29:04.630 --> 01:29:08.870
public schools as a shining
example of black reconstruction.

01:29:08.870 --> 01:29:11.610
The story he tells is of how in the south,

01:29:11.610 --> 01:29:13.530
after emancipation with the formation

01:29:13.530 --> 01:29:16.900
of the Freedman's Bureau,
there was a hunger

01:29:16.900 --> 01:29:20.610
among freed slaves for
education for their children,

01:29:20.610 --> 01:29:23.830
and what existed primarily
in the south were not

01:29:23.830 --> 01:29:26.573
what he calls the common
school or the public school.

01:29:28.025 --> 01:29:29.360
And it is out of the meager resources

01:29:29.360 --> 01:29:33.540
of the Freedman's Bureau that
we get in the American south

01:29:33.540 --> 01:29:37.007
the public school as we
now know it in the south,

01:29:37.007 --> 01:29:42.007
and for all children of
all races and all classes.

01:29:43.015 --> 01:29:47.860
And he talks about sort of
a state of reconstruction

01:29:47.860 --> 01:29:51.030
built out of the uprising of the black man

01:29:51.030 --> 01:29:54.530
with these dreams of
freedom, and for him then,

01:29:54.530 --> 01:29:56.510
the formation of the public school

01:29:56.510 --> 01:29:59.400
in the part of the country
where it didn't have precedence

01:29:59.400 --> 01:30:02.200
was one of the most important parts

01:30:02.200 --> 01:30:04.433
of reconstruction and democracy.

01:30:06.910 --> 01:30:09.510
- [Student] I have a question
over here, right here.

01:30:10.640 --> 01:30:13.810
So I think one thing that connects all of

01:30:13.810 --> 01:30:18.810
the four speakers is
that, a desire for freedom

01:30:19.238 --> 01:30:21.300
or a desire to step outside of these

01:30:21.300 --> 01:30:23.610
social, economic and political systems

01:30:23.610 --> 01:30:27.110
that restrict that freedom,
but I think my question is

01:30:27.110 --> 01:30:30.960
is how can we find freedom within that,

01:30:30.960 --> 01:30:32.787
or can we find freedom at all?

01:30:55.890 --> 01:30:58.270
- [Student] Hi, I'd like
to ask a follow-up question

01:30:58.270 --> 01:31:01.160
to that, because it seems
like all of these things,

01:31:01.160 --> 01:31:04.360
in talking about freedom, we
have to talk about bravery

01:31:04.360 --> 01:31:07.480
and the opposite side of that, like fear,

01:31:07.480 --> 01:31:11.710
so how do you face that fear

01:31:11.710 --> 01:31:13.770
when you're handling these situations,

01:31:13.770 --> 01:31:15.320
when you're putting yourself on

01:31:16.203 --> 01:31:18.080
the brink of what's your security

01:31:18.080 --> 01:31:20.860
to face up against some of these issues?

01:31:20.860 --> 01:31:23.230
- That's such a great question
and I think it sort of

01:31:23.230 --> 01:31:26.120
begins to, gives us a different angle

01:31:26.120 --> 01:31:27.670
on the questions we're hearing.

01:31:28.741 --> 01:31:31.040
So Seanna raised Colin Kaepernick,

01:31:31.040 --> 01:31:33.850
and for a while my pinned tweet

01:31:33.850 --> 01:31:38.170
was about what it might mean
for social justice-oriented

01:31:38.170 --> 01:31:40.193
urban planners to take a knee.

01:31:41.270 --> 01:31:43.170
What would be the sacrifices

01:31:43.170 --> 01:31:45.323
that we are willing to undertake?

01:31:46.400 --> 01:31:50.520
Because his act of
defiance, his insistence

01:31:50.520 --> 01:31:55.520
on making visible black
death, has come at a price.

01:31:58.340 --> 01:32:00.550
And one can say, of course,
now it's all been made right

01:32:00.550 --> 01:32:02.350
by Nike, and let's not talk about Nike

01:32:02.350 --> 01:32:03.823
and racial capitalism, right?

01:32:05.640 --> 01:32:08.043
But that aside, it's quite clear

01:32:08.043 --> 01:32:13.043
that Kaepernick will not play
football again in the NFL.

01:32:14.876 --> 01:32:16.000
And what it's made evident is of course,

01:32:16.000 --> 01:32:18.463
the plantation economy that the NFL is,

01:32:19.822 --> 01:32:24.250
so he's taken a knee and
there's been a sacrifice

01:32:24.250 --> 01:32:28.020
and so I think that is a
very important question

01:32:28.020 --> 01:32:30.300
around what are those sacrifices

01:32:30.300 --> 01:32:32.920
and one sees extraordinary sacrifices

01:32:32.920 --> 01:32:34.960
on the front lines of freedom.

01:32:34.960 --> 01:32:39.050
I'm very interested often
in what tenured faculty,

01:32:39.050 --> 01:32:41.070
who I think are some of the most protected

01:32:41.070 --> 01:32:44.290
livelihoods and bodies in
the country at the moment,

01:32:44.290 --> 01:32:47.130
what is the knee, are we
willing to take a knee

01:32:47.130 --> 01:32:48.633
and for what purpose?

01:32:49.871 --> 01:32:53.038
(audience applauding)

01:32:57.350 --> 01:32:59.230
- [Student] Hi, hello,
and thank you to everyone

01:32:59.230 --> 01:33:01.750
for sharing their perspectives on freedom.

01:33:01.750 --> 01:33:04.120
This question's primarily
to Professor Roy,

01:33:04.120 --> 01:33:07.740
but feel free for anyone to answer it.

01:33:07.740 --> 01:33:10.530
What role does architecture
play in designing

01:33:10.530 --> 01:33:13.023
more equitable and more free cities?

01:33:14.565 --> 01:33:16.731
- And you're asking a person
who's not an architect.

01:33:16.731 --> 01:33:18.031
(laughing)

01:33:18.031 --> 01:33:21.180
There's always this
fight between architects

01:33:21.180 --> 01:33:24.340
and urban planners about
who produces the city.

01:33:24.340 --> 01:33:27.450
And I hope you all noticed
his Dodgers t-shirt.

01:33:27.450 --> 01:33:29.473
Yeah? Okay.

01:33:34.279 --> 01:33:36.850
So I think the question
about the role of architects

01:33:36.850 --> 01:33:39.030
or urban planners goes
back to the questions

01:33:39.030 --> 01:33:40.980
we've heard repeatedly.

01:33:40.980 --> 01:33:44.950
So if we think about
architecture and urban planning

01:33:44.950 --> 01:33:47.530
as professions and disciplines
that have a history

01:33:47.530 --> 01:33:51.673
somewhat different than,
perhaps, the history of art,

01:33:52.690 --> 01:33:54.960
but if we subject them to the same sort of

01:33:54.960 --> 01:33:58.350
institutional critiques, then we arrive

01:33:58.350 --> 01:34:02.020
at a quite dismal place around our role

01:34:02.020 --> 01:34:04.123
in designing equitable cities.

01:34:05.049 --> 01:34:07.100
So I can't speak about
and for architecture,

01:34:07.100 --> 01:34:09.533
but particularly can't
speak for architecture.

01:34:09.533 --> 01:34:11.457
I can speak about it.

01:34:11.457 --> 01:34:13.390
But let me talk about urban planning,

01:34:13.390 --> 01:34:16.170
and particularly because
this quarter I'm teaching

01:34:16.170 --> 01:34:18.690
the Histories and Theories
of Urban Planning class

01:34:18.690 --> 01:34:20.687
that all first year master
students in urban planning

01:34:20.687 --> 01:34:23.240
and all first year PhD students take,

01:34:23.240 --> 01:34:25.140
and my students keep
wanting me to give them

01:34:25.140 --> 01:34:28.659
a message of hope, and I'm
like, there is no hope.

01:34:28.659 --> 01:34:30.981
(audience laughing)

01:34:30.981 --> 01:34:34.480
So to me, that place of
agency then, to call it that,

01:34:34.480 --> 01:34:39.480
comes from a place of
critique and a historitization

01:34:41.990 --> 01:34:45.610
that recognizes that the
landscapes of segregation

01:34:45.610 --> 01:34:47.840
that my students and I want to dismantle

01:34:48.790 --> 01:34:51.453
were produced by our profession.

01:34:53.850 --> 01:34:56.010
These weren't unintended effects,

01:34:56.010 --> 01:34:58.363
these weren't, oops we made a mistake.

01:34:59.770 --> 01:35:02.570
This was the intention of urban planning

01:35:02.570 --> 01:35:05.060
for much of the 20th century.

01:35:05.060 --> 01:35:07.300
And if we start from that place,

01:35:07.300 --> 01:35:11.390
then we get to a different
set of discussions

01:35:11.390 --> 01:35:14.840
about the agency of urban
planning and urban planners

01:35:14.840 --> 01:35:17.210
in building equitable landscapes.

01:35:17.210 --> 01:35:20.053
One of the things I'm very
interested in at the moment,

01:35:20.944 --> 01:35:22.610
taking a cue from the
movement of Black Lives

01:35:22.610 --> 01:35:25.250
and their national
platform, is how we must

01:35:25.250 --> 01:35:28.810
think about reparations,
and I like to think

01:35:28.810 --> 01:35:32.248
about reparations not just as acts

01:35:32.248 --> 01:35:35.290
in relation to specific communities,

01:35:35.290 --> 01:35:37.360
but what might it mean for the discipline

01:35:37.360 --> 01:35:40.580
and profession of urban
planning to make reparations

01:35:40.580 --> 01:35:44.570
for the redlining and environmental
racism that we produced?

01:35:44.570 --> 01:35:49.080
If that's a starting point, how
then do we think differently

01:35:49.080 --> 01:35:51.280
about our role in
producing equitable cities

01:35:51.280 --> 01:35:55.223
not as good intentions,
not as benevolence,

01:35:56.606 --> 01:36:01.010
but from a place that
recognizes our history

01:36:01.010 --> 01:36:02.403
in introducing segregation.

01:36:05.750 --> 01:36:07.777
- [Student] I had a question over here.

01:36:07.777 --> 01:36:09.400
So there were a few comments
that I heard you guys make

01:36:09.400 --> 01:36:11.370
for the questions and
also from the speakers

01:36:11.370 --> 01:36:14.510
about how there's no possible
way that we can be free

01:36:14.510 --> 01:36:18.380
until everyone has freedom,
but I personally think

01:36:18.380 --> 01:36:21.550
that with all the
unspoken rules in society

01:36:21.550 --> 01:36:24.380
and the belief that
people have in their own

01:36:24.380 --> 01:36:26.360
aberrant definitions of
freedom, there's no way

01:36:26.360 --> 01:36:29.310
for all of those things to
align, so I'm not saying

01:36:29.310 --> 01:36:32.590
there's a point to giving
up that fight for freedom,

01:36:32.590 --> 01:36:34.963
but do you think there's
freedom in resistance?

01:36:37.913 --> 01:36:38.746
- [Seanna] Sure, well.

01:36:40.810 --> 01:36:43.300
What I meant to be saying
is that I don't think

01:36:43.300 --> 01:36:47.470
we can fully achieve our
potential to be free together

01:36:47.470 --> 01:36:51.162
until everyone is enabled, for example,

01:36:51.162 --> 01:36:54.890
to live free of intense
material insecurity,

01:36:54.890 --> 01:36:59.400
or the risk of discrimination
or coercion or domination,

01:36:59.400 --> 01:37:04.400
but all of us in a variety
of ways, can be partly free.

01:37:04.870 --> 01:37:07.967
We can exercise freedom of thought,

01:37:07.967 --> 01:37:12.100
we can exercise freedom of
speech to limited degrees,

01:37:12.100 --> 01:37:16.180
subject to a variety
of insidious influences

01:37:16.180 --> 01:37:18.430
on our minds through advertising,

01:37:18.430 --> 01:37:23.258
through limited channels of communication,

01:37:23.258 --> 01:37:28.258
but we all have that ability to engage in

01:37:28.530 --> 01:37:32.800
various forms of freedom,
including resistance

01:37:32.800 --> 01:37:36.780
and the way I like to be a
little more hopeful, perhaps,

01:37:36.780 --> 01:37:41.770
is to think that we probably
aren't going to achieve

01:37:41.770 --> 01:37:45.560
full justice in our lifetime,
but we're gonna see progress

01:37:45.560 --> 01:37:50.560
if we try, and we try as a
collective, and contributing

01:37:53.470 --> 01:37:57.720
to our freedom and the
freedom of future generations

01:37:58.590 --> 01:38:01.600
is a way of being free,
it's a way of being

01:38:01.600 --> 01:38:06.600
part of a historical project
that culminates in justice,

01:38:06.830 --> 01:38:09.533
assuming we solve the
climate change problem.

01:38:09.533 --> 01:38:12.407
(audience laughing quietly)

01:38:12.407 --> 01:38:16.100
But all these efforts to be
free are, I agree with you,

01:38:16.100 --> 01:38:18.793
an aspect of exercising freedom.

01:38:19.880 --> 01:38:22.200
And I want to say this one other thing

01:38:22.200 --> 01:38:25.760
to the person who asked
the question about bravery.

01:38:25.760 --> 01:38:27.974
I want to say that all
of you who have spoken

01:38:27.974 --> 01:38:29.670
have been very brave.

01:38:29.670 --> 01:38:33.156
I know that it's very
hard as a student to talk.

01:38:33.156 --> 01:38:35.510
I'm a shy person, it's
hard for me to be here

01:38:36.939 --> 01:38:40.160
but although you might
start thinking about

01:38:40.160 --> 01:38:42.510
the large sacrifices you might make,

01:38:42.510 --> 01:38:45.530
I want to encourage you to
use the freedom that you have,

01:38:45.530 --> 01:38:49.490
you all have the freedom
to participate in classes,

01:38:49.490 --> 01:38:51.770
to talk to friends, to talk to colleagues,

01:38:51.770 --> 01:38:55.380
to talk to faculty members,
and all of those conversation

01:38:55.380 --> 01:38:57.590
where you ask "What's on your mind,"

01:38:57.590 --> 01:39:01.410
rather than what you think
you should say are always,

01:39:01.410 --> 01:39:04.210
you can start to kind of push the envelope

01:39:04.210 --> 01:39:05.790
and ask yourself, what am I really

01:39:05.790 --> 01:39:09.540
gonna be free to be able
to do, and you'll practice

01:39:09.540 --> 01:39:13.710
being a citizen and participating
in this collective project

01:39:13.710 --> 01:39:16.693
of aspiring to liberation.

01:39:20.388 --> 01:39:23.555
(audience applauding)

01:39:26.826 --> 01:39:28.330
- [Student] I have a question.

01:39:28.330 --> 01:39:29.580
I'm sorry to...

01:39:32.157 --> 01:39:34.990
So my question was
mostly from Lauren's work

01:39:35.940 --> 01:39:40.020
about Buddhists subverting the messages

01:39:40.020 --> 01:39:43.060
that the software industry gives us,

01:39:43.060 --> 01:39:45.600
and I was just wondering
if any of you guys

01:39:45.600 --> 01:39:49.770
really had an opinion
about the contrast between

01:39:49.770 --> 01:39:53.680
the message that the
tech industry gives us,

01:39:53.680 --> 01:39:55.820
which is that we're giving
you this new gadget,

01:39:55.820 --> 01:39:59.590
it's gonna free you,
and the actual effects

01:39:59.590 --> 01:40:03.570
that the industry has on the
communities it's embedded in,

01:40:03.570 --> 01:40:07.240
which tends to be this very
extreme social stratification

01:40:07.240 --> 01:40:09.590
between the engineers who work there

01:40:09.590 --> 01:40:13.230
and the people who live
within the communities

01:40:13.230 --> 01:40:14.680
that are now being displaced.

01:40:19.266 --> 01:40:21.800
- Yes, I think it's a huge problem.

01:40:21.800 --> 01:40:25.400
I think one of the
things that the industry

01:40:25.400 --> 01:40:28.780
has worked really hard to
do is to elevate the people

01:40:28.780 --> 01:40:31.530
making these technologies,
to make them seem very elite

01:40:32.700 --> 01:40:36.570
when actually, a lot of you
are sort of hackers already

01:40:36.570 --> 01:40:38.770
in the way that you figure
out how to use your apps

01:40:38.770 --> 01:40:41.000
and it doesn't work or it
doesn't update and you figure out

01:40:41.000 --> 01:40:44.632
how to reappropriate it
for your own purpose.

01:40:44.632 --> 01:40:45.960
Or maybe some of you have learned to code

01:40:45.960 --> 01:40:48.250
or learned to design or
learned to build things,

01:40:48.250 --> 01:40:50.490
and so it's not that
different but they want to

01:40:50.490 --> 01:40:54.050
draw this line between the
user and the developer,

01:40:54.050 --> 01:40:57.050
user and a producer, and I think that

01:40:57.050 --> 01:40:58.960
one of the best things you can do

01:40:58.960 --> 01:41:01.570
is to start breaking down that line,

01:41:01.570 --> 01:41:03.481
because as soon as that doesn't exist--

01:41:03.481 --> 01:41:05.786
(audience applauding)

01:41:05.786 --> 01:41:06.619
Yeah!

01:41:06.619 --> 01:41:07.870
Because as soon as that doesn't exist,

01:41:07.870 --> 01:41:09.360
then it doesn't make sense anymore

01:41:09.360 --> 01:41:10.690
for just a small group of people

01:41:10.690 --> 01:41:14.023
to live in Silicon Valley
or actually, San Francisco.

01:41:16.210 --> 01:41:19.900
- Can I just say that
someone who doesn't study

01:41:19.900 --> 01:41:23.413
technological capitalism,
that studies cities in which

01:41:23.413 --> 01:41:26.233
technological capitalism takes root,

01:41:27.221 --> 01:41:31.700
on one hand we can think
about the forms of enclosure

01:41:31.700 --> 01:41:35.650
that have been put at
work, an enclosure of

01:41:35.650 --> 01:41:39.200
the digital commons, but
an enclosure of our cities

01:41:39.200 --> 01:41:42.800
so I spend much of my academic career

01:41:42.800 --> 01:41:45.640
in Berkeley and Oakland and San Francisco,

01:41:45.640 --> 01:41:48.850
and the San Francisco Bay
area has been devastated

01:41:48.850 --> 01:41:51.270
by technological capitalism.

01:41:51.270 --> 01:41:54.240
The forms of gentrification
and displacement

01:41:54.240 --> 01:41:57.310
that have been unleashed,
not just simply by

01:41:57.310 --> 01:42:00.450
technological capitalism
as in big tech companies,

01:42:00.450 --> 01:42:04.120
but the state subsidies,
right, to these companies

01:42:04.120 --> 01:42:06.260
are incredible, and there
are some very important

01:42:06.260 --> 01:42:08.880
propositions on the ballot,
local propositions on the ballot

01:42:08.880 --> 01:42:13.880
in San Francisco coming up,
particularly around a tax

01:42:14.530 --> 01:42:17.850
on tech companies that would help fund

01:42:17.850 --> 01:42:21.980
shelters for the homeless, and the CEOs

01:42:21.980 --> 01:42:23.930
of some of our favorite companies,

01:42:23.930 --> 01:42:26.370
and I'm thoroughly complicit
here because I use Twitter

01:42:26.370 --> 01:42:29.990
all the time, but the
CEO of Twitter and others

01:42:29.990 --> 01:42:33.593
have had some of the most
horrible things to say

01:42:33.593 --> 01:42:36.690
about homeless men and
women, and have taken

01:42:36.690 --> 01:42:41.070
very strong positions
against any sort of taxation

01:42:41.070 --> 01:42:44.550
of tech wealth, particularly to help those

01:42:44.550 --> 01:42:47.403
who are facing housing
precarity and homelessness.

01:42:48.438 --> 01:42:50.180
So this remains a very real concern,

01:42:50.180 --> 01:42:53.340
sort of the Silicon
Valley effect, if you will

01:42:53.340 --> 01:42:56.386
on some of the processes that I was

01:42:56.386 --> 01:42:57.786
talking about earlier today.

01:42:59.080 --> 01:43:00.960
- Everyone, I'm gonna
have to wrap it up now.

01:43:00.960 --> 01:43:03.003
I've just had a chance to see the clock.

01:43:03.891 --> 01:43:05.390
I want to thank everybody
for coming in this evening,

01:43:05.390 --> 01:43:06.470
as we do every week.

01:43:06.470 --> 01:43:09.410
I'd like to close the session
and turn to our guests

01:43:09.410 --> 01:43:11.460
to see if any of you have anything to say

01:43:11.460 --> 01:43:13.740
as a closing statement,
offer you the opportunity

01:43:13.740 --> 01:43:17.080
to say something if it
hasn't been said yet.

01:43:17.080 --> 01:43:20.640
And otherwise, we will
close the evening out.

01:43:20.640 --> 01:43:23.540
Is there anything that any
of you would like to...

01:43:23.540 --> 01:43:25.610
- I guess I just wanted to say
that I've been sitting here

01:43:25.610 --> 01:43:30.610
feeling like the vastness
of the collective inequality

01:43:31.820 --> 01:43:34.990
and disparity is sometimes overwhelming,

01:43:34.990 --> 01:43:37.360
and this question of how can we be free

01:43:37.360 --> 01:43:40.010
until everyone's free, and
when is that gonna happen,

01:43:40.870 --> 01:43:44.580
and where is the hope, and I think for me,

01:43:44.580 --> 01:43:47.840
thinking about my own work,
a lot of it comes out,

01:43:47.840 --> 01:43:49.940
I'm obsessed with this idea of control

01:43:49.940 --> 01:43:52.710
and social expectations, and
a lot of that comes out of

01:43:52.710 --> 01:43:55.340
an experience of when I
was a really young child

01:43:55.340 --> 01:43:59.250
and I felt coerced into doing something

01:43:59.250 --> 01:44:03.710
by an older adult, and
ever since just fascinated

01:44:03.710 --> 01:44:05.810
by this idea that nobody
was holding me down

01:44:05.810 --> 01:44:07.740
but I felt I had no other options,

01:44:07.740 --> 01:44:09.840
and so for me sometimes I see myself

01:44:09.840 --> 01:44:11.670
playing out the same
dynamic, I'm setting up

01:44:11.670 --> 01:44:14.220
these systems so someone can control me,

01:44:14.220 --> 01:44:17.810
and I've made that kind
of, set this all up

01:44:17.810 --> 01:44:19.233
for myself in some way.

01:44:20.575 --> 01:44:22.060
And on one hand, I can
think that it's twisted

01:44:22.060 --> 01:44:24.470
and on the other hand I
think, well, I found some way

01:44:24.470 --> 01:44:27.870
to have some piece of control
back, some kind of agency,

01:44:27.870 --> 01:44:30.990
even if I'm replaying out these things,

01:44:30.990 --> 01:44:32.770
to mean I have some hand in it now.

01:44:32.770 --> 01:44:35.010
So maybe one thing I've
been thinking about

01:44:35.010 --> 01:44:39.140
with all this conversation
is, we absolutely need to

01:44:39.140 --> 01:44:42.560
keep thinking about how
do these larger system,

01:44:42.560 --> 01:44:44.430
what role can we play within them

01:44:44.430 --> 01:44:46.525
and how can we change them?

01:44:46.525 --> 01:44:47.930
At the same time, how can
you get a handle on something

01:44:47.930 --> 01:44:50.050
so that you do feel like
you have a sense of power

01:44:50.050 --> 01:44:51.683
to actually enact the change?

01:44:52.857 --> 01:44:53.826
- Thank you.

01:44:53.826 --> 01:44:54.737
Andrea?

01:44:54.737 --> 01:44:57.904
(audience applauding)

01:45:02.554 --> 01:45:03.387
- Well there were
question after question of

01:45:03.387 --> 01:45:06.520
how can we be free, how
can we find freedom,

01:45:06.520 --> 01:45:11.520
and I was coming to this from
a kind of critical perspective

01:45:11.890 --> 01:45:14.820
on freedom, that is the forms of freedom

01:45:15.810 --> 01:45:19.390
and discourses of freedom that
are also highly ideological

01:45:19.390 --> 01:45:22.830
and partial and have
existed over centuries

01:45:22.830 --> 01:45:24.513
as forms of privilege.

01:45:25.410 --> 01:45:28.940
So the important point
of, we can't be free

01:45:28.940 --> 01:45:32.630
until everyone's free, I
was on a panel years ago

01:45:32.630 --> 01:45:36.950
about censorship that wasn't
picketed but leafleted

01:45:36.950 --> 01:45:41.138
by adjunct faculty who
had tried to organize,

01:45:41.138 --> 01:45:45.490
and I began that statement
by quoting Eugene Debs,

01:45:45.490 --> 01:45:48.840
the American socialist,
who said famously...

01:45:50.199 --> 01:45:51.980
Oh god, what did he say?

01:45:51.980 --> 01:45:53.373
Now I can't remember.

01:45:54.683 --> 01:45:55.516
Oh, come on.

01:45:55.516 --> 01:45:57.333
Oh, don't do this to me.

01:45:58.470 --> 01:46:01.667
The last line is, "As long
as there's a soul in chains,

01:46:01.667 --> 01:46:04.677
"as long as there's a man
in chains, I am not free,"

01:46:06.348 --> 01:46:08.907
but "As long as there is
a lower class, I am of it.

01:46:08.907 --> 01:46:12.587
"As long as there is a
criminal element, I am in it.

01:46:12.587 --> 01:46:16.402
"As long as there is a man
in chains, I am not free."

01:46:16.402 --> 01:46:17.485
- [Brett] Wow

01:46:18.325 --> 01:46:21.595
- So I'll close with that.
(audience applauding)

01:46:21.595 --> 01:46:23.178
- Seanna or Ananya?

01:46:25.408 --> 01:46:26.647
- [Seanna] I just want
to say the following.

01:46:26.647 --> 01:46:29.020
These are such important topics,

01:46:29.020 --> 01:46:32.340
and I've been kind of
urging that we think about

01:46:32.340 --> 01:46:36.980
more conversation, but the
question that the student asked

01:46:36.980 --> 01:46:39.840
reminded me of the fact that

01:46:39.840 --> 01:46:42.430
technology has empowered
conversations between us

01:46:42.430 --> 01:46:45.940
internationally and
notionally, immediately

01:46:45.940 --> 01:46:50.940
in ways that were inconceivable
40 or 50 years ago,

01:46:52.370 --> 01:46:56.020
but it has also created
intense social expectations

01:46:56.020 --> 01:46:58.240
of certain kinds of immediate exchange,

01:46:58.240 --> 01:46:59.610
and there's an argument to be made

01:46:59.610 --> 01:47:03.790
that the quality of our discourse
has really deteriorated.

01:47:03.790 --> 01:47:07.080
We write fewer letters,
we write quicker emails,

01:47:07.080 --> 01:47:10.473
we write 160-character communications,

01:47:11.400 --> 01:47:16.400
and there's another side to
the technological capitalism

01:47:16.480 --> 01:47:18.630
which is that all of these changes

01:47:18.630 --> 01:47:21.500
were made in a non-democratic way

01:47:21.500 --> 01:47:24.560
and mostly by companies
for their own profit,

01:47:24.560 --> 01:47:27.210
and if we're thinking a little bit

01:47:27.210 --> 01:47:31.040
about democracy and bringing
democracy to corporations

01:47:31.040 --> 01:47:34.360
as a way to think about improving
the discourse between us,

01:47:34.360 --> 01:47:35.850
but more practically, 'cause some of you

01:47:35.850 --> 01:47:38.930
want a practical thing,
let me just say this.

01:47:38.930 --> 01:47:41.450
It feels weird that we've
been having this conversation

01:47:41.450 --> 01:47:46.220
about conversations, but (laughing)

01:47:46.220 --> 01:47:48.070
very few of us in the room have talked.

01:47:48.070 --> 01:47:49.960
If anyone wants to talk
to me about this stuff,

01:47:49.960 --> 01:47:51.980
you're welcome to come to my office hours.

01:47:51.980 --> 01:47:54.572
They're on the web, I'd love to meet you

01:47:54.572 --> 01:47:56.470
and talk to you and hear what you thought.

01:47:56.470 --> 01:47:57.447
- Thank you.

01:47:57.447 --> 01:47:59.917
(audience applauding)

01:47:59.917 --> 01:48:00.750
Thank you.

01:48:01.831 --> 01:48:03.410
Ananya, any closing?

01:48:03.410 --> 01:48:08.410
- So, I wanted to end with a
very flawed form of freedom

01:48:09.300 --> 01:48:12.560
that we live with and
which serves as a premise

01:48:12.560 --> 01:48:15.200
for this sort of gathering
which is academic freedom

01:48:16.200 --> 01:48:21.037
and with the ascendance of Mr. 45,

01:48:22.700 --> 01:48:24.773
I refuse to call him President,

01:48:26.920 --> 01:48:29.460
I think it's become
ever more apparent to me

01:48:29.460 --> 01:48:32.350
that academic freedom
is important, precious.

01:48:32.350 --> 01:48:35.110
It's always been thoroughly limited

01:48:35.110 --> 01:48:38.460
and as I said, deeply
flawed, and yet in many ways

01:48:38.460 --> 01:48:42.080
the power that we hold is
that of academic freedom,

01:48:42.080 --> 01:48:44.860
not just those of us
who are tenured faculty

01:48:44.860 --> 01:48:47.350
but in belonging to
this incredibly powerful

01:48:50.486 --> 01:48:52.670
knowledge-producing
institution, we are a part

01:48:52.670 --> 01:48:54.510
of academic freedom, and I would ask us

01:48:54.510 --> 01:48:57.980
to think about how we use that freedom

01:48:57.980 --> 01:49:02.403
to make possible wider
projects of freedom.

01:49:03.550 --> 01:49:05.576
- Perfect, thank you Ananya, thank you.

01:49:05.576 --> 01:49:07.898
(audience applauding)

01:49:07.898 --> 01:49:10.210
thank you everybody so much for coming in.

01:49:10.210 --> 01:49:12.460
Please join me in thanking Seanna, Andrea,

01:49:12.460 --> 01:49:15.681
Lauren, and Ananya for
coming in this evening,

01:49:15.681 --> 01:49:16.580
for a terrific conversation.

01:49:16.580 --> 01:49:19.873
Thank you everybody, we
will see you next Tuesday.

